<HEAD>
<TITLE>THE FULBRIGHT PROGRAM AFTER FIFTY YEARS -- CRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<img src="/crc/images/fulbrit.gif" alt="Book Cover" align="right">
<P>
<h2> The Fulbright Program After Fifty Years: From Mutual Understanding to Mutual Support</h2>
(<a href="/crc/about/pubs.html">Ordering Information</a>)<br><P>

<a href="#summ">Executive Summary</a>
<P>
<h3>Table of Contents</h3>
<ul>
<P>
I.   Overview
<P>
II. International Exchange Programs Today:  How Important Is the
Fulbright Program? 
<P>
III. &quot;Enhancing Mutual Understanding&quot;: Key to International
Peace?
<P>
IV.  Administering and Financing the Fulbright Program 
<P>
V.   The Fulbright Selection Process for Scholars and Students

<P>
VI. Enlisting the Fulbright Constituency 
<P>
VII. Past Proposed Fulbright Reforms
<P>
VIII. Some Basic Questions For the Fulbright Program
<P>
IX. Recommendations for the Future of the Fulbright Program (available below)
</ul>
<P>
<a name="summ"></a>
<h2> Executive Summary</h2>
<P>
<h3> Recommendations for the Future of the Fulbright Program</h3>
<P>
<ul>
 Policymakers need to critically re-examine the future role of
the Federal Government in sponsoring the Fulbright program of
international educational exchanges.  They will want to recognize
the program's very real accomplishments over the past half century.
 But they should question the contribution the Fulbright program
can make in a post-Cold War world.  And they should ask whether
that contribution is a national interest requiring government
funding.  This report recommends a substantial reevaluation
of the nature of the program and cites various changes that would
both continue the most valuable elements of the existing program,
while at the same time share its costs more equitably with other
countries and the academic community.
<P>
<B> 1.  Freeze Spending.</B>  The new Congress initially should
freeze spending on the Fulbright program at the existing level
and plan for a gradual reduction in future funding.  International
educational exchange is no longer a new idea requiring nurture.
 Programs that make possible overseas travel by hundreds of thousands
of scholars and students are well established throughout the world.
 It is no longer necessary to organize these programs under government
auspices and sponsorship.  As in so many other areas, private
and nonprofit institutions in civil society are the most appropriate
providers of institutional and financial support.  
<P>
 However, the Fulbright program is a prestigious program that
has been established by mutual agreements with other countries,
including our major allies and trading partners.  Consequently,
the program should continue, but grant awards should be limited
and they should be sustained in most countries by mutual and equivalent
levels of financial support.  During the past 48 years the U.S.
has provided $1.67 billion in Fulbright funding.  The time has
come to redesign the Fulbright program.  A program intended to
establish mutual understanding that is mutually beneficial should
be mutually supported.
<P>
<B> 2.  Require Foreign Contribution Levels Equal to U.S. Government
Support.</B>  Fifty binational commissions administer most of
the major Fulbright exchanges and they have made overseas Fulbright
programs a genuine collaborative endeavor.  But the mutual role
of U.S. and foreign counterparts in administering the program
should be accompanied, in most instances, by equivalent binational
financing.  
<P>
 Currently only ten countries contribute as much financial support
to the program as the United States.  The Fulbright program should
welcome an emphasis on mutuality with Western Europe, Japan and
other nations able to support joint exchanges.  Many governments,
including those of the so-called newly industrialized countries
of Asia, spend enormous sums to sponsor their students in the
United States.  Indeed, foreign governments pay about 5 percent
of the costs of all foreign students in the U.S.  They should
be willing to transfer some of these resources to the Fulbright
program.  By raising their contributions, wealthy countries would
share with the U.S. the cost of the program. 
<P>
 If these countries are unwilling to provide support at levels
equivalent to U.S. support, then the United States should reduce
its contribution to parity.  In bilateral programs where cost-sharing
is equivalent or where the U.S. contribution is less than the
foreign counterpart, U.S. support levels should not be ratcheted
upward.  Some of the funds &quot;saved&quot; by cost-sharing adjustments
should be reallocated to programs targeting former Soviet bloc
states and other newly emerging nations in Africa, the Middle
East or South Asia that lack the resources to support international
educational exchanges.  U.S. government funding can be steadily
reduced as more countries contribute their share to the program.
<P>
<B> 3.  Tighten Oversight.</B>  The Board of Foreign Scholarships,
which has responsibility for the Fulbright program, should conduct
a comprehensive review of program operations.  In particular,
the Board should initiate discussions on the above-mentioned reallocation
of program resources and on developing ways to increase foreign
government and private sources of support.  The Board and USIA
should also consider ways to involve new segments of the American
academic community.  For instance, currently only seven percent
of scholar grants go to those teaching at liberal arts colleges
and two percent of grants go to community college teachers.  There
should also be more competition in selecting the contract agencies
that actually develop the mechanisms for the review and nomination
of Fulbright candidates.
<P>
<B> 4.  De-emphasize Western Europe.</B>  Western Europe should
be de-emphasized as a destination for American scholars and students.
 Instead, the regional emphasis should move east to the emerging
democracies of the former Warsaw Pact countires.  Resources currently
allocated to Western Europe should be shifted to Central and Eastern
Europe.  This is an area of vital interest to the United States
and one where governments lack the resources and historical connections
to develop educational exchanges with us.
<P>
<B> 5.  Give Priority to U.S. Students.</B>  In allocating financial
support the Fulbright program should give priority to American
graduate students pursuing overseas studies over American senior
scholars.  For every six foreign students in the United States
one American student goes overseas.  Very few American graduate
students pursue overseas educations in countries outside Europe.
 Here is an area where Fulbright grants can provide a real incentive.
 Such grants are far more likely to have an impact on young careers
than grants to senior scholars.  Senator Fulbright is reported
to have commented pointedly in 1987 at a Fulbright alumni conference
that he had initially conceived the program for graduate students,
not faculty with their &quot;whole damn families.&quot;    
<P>
<B> 6.  Encourage Fulbright Alumni Support.</B>  The prestige
of the Fulbright program depends on its history and its distinguished
alumni.  This constituency can continue to play an important role
in facilitating international exchanges in the future.  Prominent
former Fulbright award recipients can encourage foreign governments
and private sources to provide funding.  By anticipating reduced
U.S. government support, Fulbright alumni can help sustain a program
from which personally they have greatly benefitted.  Alumni groups
in foreign countries and in the U.S. should initiate funding for
national programs, as Japanese alumni did when they established
a scholarship endowment fund.
<P>
<B> 7.  Maintain USIA Information Services.</B>  Fulbright program
officials and related USIA offices overseas should continue to
play an important and impartial role providing information on
U.S. academic opportunities and on the many nongovernment programs
providing scholarship assistance to foreign students and scholars.
 USIA library resources of college catalogues and information
on application procedures are particularly valuable, especially
in Central and Eastern Europe. 
<P>
<B> 8.  Back to Core Values:  </B>The central value of the Fulbright
program from its inception has been the prestige it has given
to America by making possible high quality international scholar
and student exchanges.  The program should return to its historic
roots as a small and important program with a clear mission. 
The total number of grants may diminish, but the Fulbright program
can foster academic exchanges that would not otherwise occur,
especially in newly emerging democratic countries.  Just as the
Fulbright program contributed to the reconstruction of post-World
War II Europe fifty years ago, so can it assist today in the construction
of a post-Cold War world.
</ul>
</blockquote>
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
