<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Great Philanthropists and the Problems
of Donor Intent -- CRC</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<img src="/crc/images/wooster.gif" alt="Book Cover" align="right">
<P>
<h2>The Great Philanthropists and the Problems
of Donor Intent</h2>
(<a href="/crc/about/pubs.html">Ordering Information</a>)<br><P>
<a href="#summ">Executive Summary</a>
<P>
<h3>Table of Contents</h3>
<ul>
<B>Preface</B>
<P>
<B>Introduction </B><I>American Philanthropy and the Problems
of Donor Intent</I>
<P>
<B>Section One </B><I>The Rockefeller Legacy</I>
<P>
<B>Section Two </B><I>Undermining Donor Intent</I>
<P>
<B>Section Three </B><I>Preserving Donor Intent</I>
<P>
<B>Section Four </B><I>A Legal History of Donor Intent</I>
<P>
<B>Conclusion </B><I>What Donors Can Do</I>
<P>
<B>Notes</B>
<P>
<B>Index </B>
</ul>
<P>
<a name="summ"></a>

<B>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</B>
<P>
 
<P>
  How can those who wish to create a charitable foundation best
ensure that their wishes will be followed after their deaths?
<P>
 In this important and timely book, Martin Morse Wooster provides
a well-reasoned answer to this question, as well as a fascinating
overview of the individuals, ideas, and beliefs that inspired
the creation of some of America's largest foundations. In some
cases, the intentions of those who created great philanthropies
have been faithfully adhered to by trustees. Unfortunately, however,
in most cases those intentions have been either ignored or brazenly
violated. 
<P>
Drawing on an examination of foundations that have either followed
or rejected the beliefs and wishes of their founders, Wooster
outlines a set of principles that wealthy donors should bear in
mind when considering the creation of a foundation. Given that
the &quot;baby boom&quot; generation is expected to transfer an
estimated $8 to $10 trillion over the next few decades--and that
a good portion of this wealth may go to philanthropy--Wooster's
guidelines may serve to prevent donors from bequeathing wealth
in ways they would regret. 
</ul>
</blockquote>
</BODY>

</HTML>
