<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Henry Consent Decree</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT<BR>
FOR THE SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF OHIO<BR>
EASTERN DIVISION<BR></CENTER>
<PRE>
HENRY PAINTING COMPANY, ET AL.,

Plaintiffs,						Case No. C2-94-0196

-v-							JUDGE SMITH

THE OHIO STATE UNIVERSITY, ET AL.,

Defendants.
</PRE>
<CENTER><U>CONSENT DECREE</U></CENTER>
<P>This action was filed by Plaintiffs on March 10, 1994 seeking a
judgment declaring unconstitutional certain provisions of the
Ohio Minority Business Enterprise Act (Ohio Rev. Code SS 122.71,
123.141 and 125.081)("OMBEA").  Plaintiffs allege that Defendants
have unconstitutionally discriminated against them on the basis
of race in the awarding of contracts for painting only to
minority businesses.  These allegations were denied by
Defendants.  The Court's jurisdiction is invoked pursuant to 28
U.S.C. SS 2201 and 2202.   Plaintiffs also seek a permanent
injunction preventing Defendants from applying or enforcing the
OMBEA, and monetary damages under 24 U.S.C. SS 2000d and 2000d-7.
Nothing contained in this Consent Decree, and no actions taken by
Defendants with respect to this Decree, shall be treated         
as an admission of liability by Defendants.

    <P>      The Plaintiffs and Defendants, in good faith, desire to
amicably compromise, settle, and resolve their dispute so as to
avoid the costs and inconvenience of further litigation. 
Accordingly, the parties have consented to the entry of this
Consent Decree subject to approval and entry by the Court.<BR><BR>

I. <U>INJUNCTION</U>

<P>IT IS ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED that Defendants, their
agents, employees, successors and all persons in active concert
or participation with any of them are hereby enjoined from:

<P>A.   Considering race, color, national origin, gender, social or
economic disadvantage, or any factor other than standard State
procurement policies and practices, in awarding painting
contracts at The Ohio State University.<BR><BR>

II. <U>NOTICE</U>

<P>IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that Defendant, The Ohio State University
will notify and undertake an educational program as to its
obligations under the Consent Decree as follows:


  <P>        A. Provide a copy of this Decree to the members of The
Ohio State University's Board of Trustees, University officials, 
and all employees responsible for the awarding and/or selection
of painting contracts at the University within 30 days of the
entry of this Decree.  For the duration of this Decree, a copy of
this Decree shall be provided to all new members of the Board of
Trustees, and any new employee responsible for the awarding
and/or selection of painting contractors, or who assume these
responsibilities, within thirty (30) days of taking the office or
assuming such responsibilities.<BR><BR>

III. <U>MONETARY PAYMENT</U>

<P>IT IS ALSO ORDERED, that on or by April 30, 1996, Defendant The
Ohio State University shall deliver a certified check payable to
Henry Painting Company and Jerry Henry, jointly, in the amount of
Two Hundred and Forty Thousand Dollars and 00/100 ($240,000.00). 
The payment of this sum is in full settlement of any claims that
Plaintiffs have or ever had against Defendants.


<P>IT IS ALSO ORDERED that on or by April 30, 1996, Defendant The
Ohio State University shall deliver a certified check payable to
the Center for Individual Rights in the amount of One Hundred
Twenty Eight Thousand Dollars and 00/100 ($128,000.00).  The
payment of this sum represents full payment of Plaintiffs,
reasonable attorney fees in this case.


  <P>        Plaintiffs shall also execute, on or by April 30, 1996,
a release signifying that the amounts received pursuant to this
order represent full and complete compensation for all alleged
injuries and constitutes full settlement of any claims (including
claims for costs and attorneys' fees) that may have related to
the subject matter of this lawsuit.<BR><BR>

IV. <U>REMEDIES FOR NON-PERFORMANCE</U>

<P>     The parties to this Consent Decree shall endeavor in good
faith to resolve informally any differences regarding
interpretation of and compliance with this order prior to
bringing such matters to the Court for resolution.  However, in
the event of a failure by the Defendants, whether willful or
otherwise, to perform any obligation imposed by, or otherwise
comply with this Decree, they will be subject to all sanctions
and remedies authorized by law-or equity.  The Court shall retain
jurisdiction to enforce the terms of this order.  After five
years from entry of this Order, Defendants may move for
dissolution of the decree and dismissal of the case.  The Court
will resolve that motion pursuant to the legal and equitable
standards governing such proceedings.

<P>IT IS SO ORDERED.<BR><BR><BR>



GEORGE C. SMITH, JUDGE<BR>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT<BR>
<BR>


The undersigned consent to entry of this Consent Decree.<BR><BR>



FOR PLAINTIFFS:<BR><BR>

/S/ Michael Carvin<BR><BR>


FOR DEFENDANTS:<BR><BR>

/s/  Fred G. Pressley, Jr. per approval by the Attorney General 
</BODY>
