<DOCNO>WT20-B16-30</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA031-000656-B024-351</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.atr.org:80/claremont/edit/inaug97.htm 204.71.237.87 19970209063650 text/html 9060
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 06:37:34 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 08-Feb-97 08:11:31 GMT
Content-length: 8875
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="Microsoft Word 97">
<TITLE>CLINTON'S CRAFT AND THE REPUBLICAN DRIFT</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY LINK="#0000ff" BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<a name="top"> </a>
<B><FONT SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">CLINTON'S CRAFT AND THE REPUBLICAN DRIFT</P>
</B></FONT><P ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="#cheath">By Charles L. Heatherly</a></P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">In his Inaugural Address President Clinton announced an armistice in the war of ideas. He declared, &quot;we have resolved for our time the great debate over the role of government.&quot;  He hailed America's new consensus: for the 21<SUP>st</SUP> century we need a government &quot;that is smaller. . . and does more with less.&quot;</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">The same day Rush Limbaugh interpreted the president's Inaugural remarks as a concession speech, and accepted the victory in his usual magnanimous fashion. That Clinton is still a liberal in his heart doesn't matter, argued Limbaugh. The war of ideas is over if liberalism can survive only in conservative garb. Clinton has retooled the Democratic party as a centrist party; thus, Republicans still have the upper hand in the shaping of the policy agenda.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">That belief has been popular among beltway conservatives for many years, but it would have more coherence if there were any Republican ideas to challenge liberalism's new cloaking device. Too many Republicans learned the wrong lesson from the 1996 campaign: they envy Clinton his success in disguising himself as a centrist, and they yearn to imitate him. In Washington these days such foolishness passes for deep thinking.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">That Clinton now occupies the high ground politically cannot be seriously disputed. The president's Inaugural Address continued the &quot;triangulation&quot; strategy that brought him success in the 1996 presidential campaign against Senator Dole, and we can expect to see that strategy again in his State of the Union speech. Dole never countered it effectively, and most congressional Republicans seem equally impotent.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Yet the Inaugural speech is also vintage Clinton in taking back with the a wink one moment what he proffered with a smile a moment before. It is in these contradictions and Clinton's hollow tokenism that Republicans should see Clinton's Achilles heel. Behind the cloak of conservative rhetoric beats the heart of a liberal, and no cloaking device can hide that for long.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Clinton's faithfulness to core liberal beliefs is clear from a close reading of his Inaugural speech. To serve his ambition to define and occupy the &quot;vital center,&quot; Clinton now seeks to be the champion of &quot;smaller government.&quot; But in what respect smaller? Well, maybe not smaller in every respect, or even in any important respect. He cautions us that &quot;where government can give Americans the power to make a real difference in their daily lives, government should do more.&quot; That small qualification will cover a multitude of new initiatives. He will strive to &quot;give all Americans an opportunity to build better lives.&quot; Thus, neither Clinton nor his liberalism are in retreat; they have merely been enjoying &quot;R and R&quot; and are now ready for renewed battle.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Republicans are beginning to understand that triangulation is not merely a defensive strategy improvised for an election campaign. It has many uses in governance. Clinton will first occupy the muddy middle of American politics, then redefine it in a way that preserves the core programs of Great Society liberalism while also allowing for incremental expansion in education, law enforcement, &quot;health security&quot; and other areas where the public still supports an activist role. This strategy will succeed absent a coherent Republican alternative.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Now in control of both houses of Congress for a second consecutive term for the first time in seventy years, Republicans appear to be utterly confused and divided about both principle and program. They await Clinton's State of the Union address in the hope that the president will propose something they can oppose. Then, after a lengthy and honorable debate, they can reach a compromise with Clinton and thus appear statesmanlike.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">It's a cool thing, this bipartisanship, not as messy and conflict-ridden as the old, uncool ideological politics. The Contract With America was decidedly uncool: it brought confrontation and then defeat in the mismanagement of the budget impasse. If the Contract With America was too risky, a contract with the paymaster is the needed corrective.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Where will all this newly acquired coolness leave the Republicans after the dust settles and the Clinton- Gore administration claims credit for whatever compromise legislation is eventually enacted? Do such pale &quot;victories&quot; provide the building blocks for expanding their majority in the 1998 congressional elections? Do they tell the citizens of the nation how a Republican government would differ from the status quo? Will such a me-too strategy give Republicans a platform for recapturing the White House in the year 2000?</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">These are the questions conservatives are asking themselves these days. The answers are not comforting, so some commentators choose to ask only questions that have easier answers. Many otherwise serious analysts trace the current Republican malaise and Clinton's popularity to the strong economy, and they see that as the underlying reason for Dole's defeat. &quot;History was on Clinton's side. What could we do?&quot; By this logic Republicans should pray for a national calamity as the surest road to the White House. </P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">The strong economy did not re-elect Bill Clinton, and it will not take a poor one to elect a Republican successor. If such were true, Republicans could pick their presidential nominee by lot, and they could write their next platform by a committee of economists and pollsters. But a party leader and presidential candidate must speak to the great issues confronting the nation, which means he must first see the great issues. They are there, waiting for the political leader who will grasp them and point the way to a recovery of our true greatness.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Clinton succeeded-with help from a rudderless Dole campaign-in avoiding those great issues and postponing that needed debate. But his victory may prove hollow if the real divisions afflicting the nation erupt elsewhere in the body politic, as is likely to happen.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Clinton's Inaugural Address was mediocre, the symbolism flat, compared to the great inaugural speeches of Washington, Lincoln, FDR, Kennedy and Reagan. That it may nonetheless succeed in its purpose-defining a new center and a new consensus that preserves the liberal welfare state from further erosion-is a sad commentary on the health of the Republican Party.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">It will take something more than economic determinism to awaken this party from its complacency and drift. That something is called leadership, and it can come only from within the ranks, not from outside. Leadership means direction, and direction requires purpose. At this moment, the Republican party doesn't have one, other than the desire to avoid another budget fiasco. The goals of &quot;expanding the base of the party&quot; and &quot;reaching out to new voters&quot; are laudable, but they are means, not ends. Will these new recruits not want to know where the party intends to take them?</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">The man who summons the Republican party to a higher purpose, as Lincoln did in championing the exclusion of slavery from new states and territories, will become its leader. And he will have a fair chance of becoming the next president-even without a stock market crash.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">&nbsp;</P>
<hr>
<a name="cheath"> </a><P ALIGN="JUSTIFY"></FONT><A HREF="mailto:cheatherly@msn.com"><FONT SIZE=2> Charles L. Heatherly</FONT></A><FONT SIZE=2> is Executive Vice President of the Claremont Institute, and a former policy official of the U.S. Department of Education and the Small Business Administration. <a href=#top>Return to top.</a></P>
<hr>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">&nbsp;</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></FONT><A HREF="http://www.claremont.org/edit.htm"><FONT SIZE=2>Editorial Page</FONT></A><FONT SIZE=2> || </FONT><A HREF="http://www.claremont.org/"><FONT SIZE=2>Home Page</FONT></A></P>
<FONT SIZE=2><P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">&nbsp;</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=1><P ALIGN="CENTER">Copyright &copy; 1997 The Claremont Institute</P></FONT></BODY>
</HTML>
