</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="Microsoft Word 97">
<TITLE>Does decisional law grant whites fewer political rights under the Fourteenth Amendment than it grants to racial minorities</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<a name="top"></a>
<B><FONT FACE="Roman" SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Does Decisional Law Grant Whites Fewer Political Rights Under the Fourteenth Amendment Than It Grants to Racial Minorities?</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">A Reply to Vikram D. Amar and Evan H. Caminker</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Roman"><P ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="#wood">By Thomas E. Wood</a></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">INTRODUCTION</P>
</B><P>On November 5, 1996, the California electorate adopted Proposition 209, otherwise known as the California Civil Rights Initiative (CCRI), by a margin of 54-46 percent.  For the purposes of the present paper, the key provisions of Proposition 209, which now comprises Article I, Section 31 of the state constitution, are as follows:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

</FONT><P>Prop. 209: <FONT SIZE=3> (a)  The state shall not discriminate against, or grant preferential treatment to, any individual or group on the basis of race, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origin in the operation of public employment, public education, or public contracting.</P>
</FONT><P ALIGN="CENTER">* * * </P>
<FONT SIZE=3><P> (f)  For the purposes of this section, &quot;state&quot; shall include, but not necessarily be limited to, the state itself, any city, county, city and county, public university system, including the University of California, community college district, school district, special district, or any other political subdivision or governmental instrumentality of or within the state.</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

</FONT><FONT FACE="Roman"><P>In an article in the <I>Hastings Constitutional Law Quarterly</I>, Vol. 23:4, Summer 1996, pp. 1-39 (&quot;Equal Protection, Unequal Political Burdens, and the CCRI&quot;), Vikram D. Amar and Evan H. Caminker argue that lower courts, at least, must hold Proposition 209 unconstitutional in light of the Supreme Court precedent <I>Washington v. Seattle School District No. 1</I> (1982), 458 U.S. 457. </P>
<P>&#9;The present paper is a response to Amar and Caminker. It is argued in this paper that under the <I>Seattle</I> precedent it is not unconstitutional for a state to use a political decisionmaking process (in this case, a statewide initiative) to constitutionalize a prohibition against race-conscious measures, even if the adoption of that policy change makes it more difficult than before for minorities to obtain legislation at lower levels of government that the Court might deem to be in their interest.  According to the analysis provided here, the <I>Seattle</I> ruling invalidates only those enactments that meet both of the following criteria: (1) the enactment addresses a racial matter; and (2) it <I>explicitly</I> alters a political decisionmaking process on that racial matter in a way that places a special burden on minorities.</P>
<P>The paper discusses <I>Crawford v. Board of Education</I> (1982), 458 U.S. 527, and finds important corroborating evidence for its analysis of <I>Seattle</I> in that decision.  It also criticizes the Amar-Caminker interpretation of <I>Seattle </I>on the grounds that it necessarily implies that minorities have political rights under the Fourteenth Amendment that the majority does not have.  The Amar-Caminker interpretation is also criticized on the grounds that it cannot be reconciled with the <I>Seattle </I>Court's clear and explicit statement that states do have the right under the federal constitution to establish race-neutral policies on racial questions.  The recent analysis of <I>Seattle </I>by U.S. District Court Judge Thelton H. Henderson, which is very similar to the Amar-Caminker interpretation and which may very well have been inspired by it, is criticized on similar grounds.<SUP>1</P>
</SUP><I><P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">WASHINGTON v. SEATTLE SCHOOL DISTRICT NO. 1</I> (1982), 458 U.S. 457</P>
</B><P>In 1978, the Seattle School District adopted a desegregation plan that made extensive use of mandatory busing.  Subsequently, a group of citizens in Seattle drafted a statewide ballot measure (Initiative 350) which, they hoped, would result in the termination of the Seattle busing plan, and of racial busing in the State of Washington generally.  The key provision of the measure read as follows:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>Init. 350: </FONT><FONT FACE="Roman" SIZE=3>Be it enacted by the People of the State of Washington:</P>
<P>Notwithstanding any other provision of law, after the effective date of this act no school board, school district, educational service district board, educational service district, or county committee, nor the superintendent of public instruction, nor the state board of education, nor any of their respective employees, agents or delegates shall directly or indirectly require any student to attend a school other than the school which is geographically nearest or next nearest the student's place of residence within the school district of his or her residence and which offers the course of study pursued by such student ...</FONT><FONT FACE="Roman">.<SUP>2</SUP><I> </P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

</I><P>In addition, the measure set out a number of broad exceptions to this requirement.  As qualified by the exceptions, the prohibition had the effect of permitting mandatory busing for every purpose <I>other</I> than that of racial balancing or integration of the schools.  The measure also proscribed the use of seven enumerated methods of indirect student assignment-among them the redefinition of attendance zones, the pairing of schools, and the use of &quot;feeder&quot; schools-which had figured in the Seattle plan. The initiative permitted racial busing in only one circumstance: it did not purport to &quot;prevent any court of competent jurisdiction from adjudicating constitutional issues relating to the public schools.&quot;<SUP>3</P>
</SUP><P>&#9;There are a couple of rather obvious differences between Proposition 209 and Initiative 350 that will figure prominently in the following discussion.</P>
<P>&#9;First, Initiative 350 did not establish a statewide policy prohibiting mandatory racial busing, and as the <I>Seattle</I> Court itself noted, it left the state legislature free to order such busing.<SUP>4</SUP>  Clearly, a measure that allows the state legislature to order mandatory racial busing fails to establish a policy against such busing.  In this respect, Initiative 350 is clearly different from Proposition 209, which is a pure policy enactment.</P>
<P>&#9;Second, Initiative 350 effectively eliminated mandatory racial busing in the State of Washington by working an explicit change in the state's political decisionmaking process--and in particular, by removing decisionmaking authority over mandatory racial busing from local school boards.  In this respect, too, it differs from Proposition 209, which has no language that alters California's political decisionmaking process in an analogous way.</P>
<P>&#9;In 1982, the <I>Seattle </I>Court held, 5 to 4, that Initiative 350 altered the political decisionmaking process in Washington State on a specifically racial question in a way that placed special burdens on minorities in that political process, and that Initiative 350 therefore violated the Fourteenth Amendment of the U.S. Constitution.<SUP>5</SUP>  The problem before us is to understand this ruling and its implications, if any, for the adjudication of the constitutionality of California's Proposition 209. </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">A DIVIDED COURT</P>
</B><P>&#9;To answer this question, it is necessary to ask whether the <I>Seattle</I> ruling entails that a policy enactment on a racial question by a higher level of government prohibiting race-conscious measures that are arguably in the interest of minorities violates the Fourteenth Amendment.  On this fundamental point, a minority of the <I>Seattle </I>Court thought it did (or might), but the Court itself did not.</P>
<P>According to Justice Powell, who wrote the minority opinion in <I>Seattle, </I>the Court's invalidation of Initiative 350 had arguably committed the Court to the following positions, which he clearly regarded as not merely untenable, but absurd:</P>
<P>&#9;(1)&#9;That the adoption of a neighborhood school policy by a local school board is permissible under the federal constitution, but that the adoption of such a policy at the <I>state</I> level violates the Fourteenth Amendment.  458 U.S. 488-489.</P>
<P>&#9;(2)&#9;That while it would be constitutionally permissible for the Seattle School District to change its mind and cancel its program of mandatory racial busing of its own volition, neither the state legislature nor the people of the State of Washington could alter what the District had decided.  458 U.S. 494.</P>
<P>&#9;(3)&#9;That the ruling barred the Supreme Court of the State of Washington from interpreting a provision of its state constitution to prohibit race-conscious school assignments, despite the fact that such a prohibition would be a facially tenable construction of that provision.  458 U.S.  499, fn. 15.<SUP>6</P>
</SUP><P>&#9;(4)&#9;That in its ruling the Court was reversing its prior dictum in <I>Regents of the University of California v. Bakke</I> (1978) that &quot;in the absence of a federal constitutional violation <I>requiring</I> [emphasis in original] race-specific remedies, a policy of strict racial neutrality by a State would violate no federal principle.&quot;  458 U.S. 491.<SUP>7</P>
</SUP><P>&#9;The passage in Powell's dissent to which the <I>Seattle </I>Court responded most directly was the following one:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

</FONT><FONT FACE="Roman" SIZE=3><P>Under [the Court's] holding the people of the State of Washington apparently are forever barred from developing a different <I>policy</I> [emphasis added] on mandatory busing where a school district previously has adopted one of its own.  This principle would not seem limited to the question of mandatory busing.  Thus, if the admissions committee of a state law school developed an affirmative-action plan that came under fire, the Court apparently would find it unconstitutional for any higher authority to intervene unless that authority traditionally dictated admissions policies...After today's decision it is unclear whether the State may <I>set policy</I> [emphasis added] in any area where a local governmental body arguably has done &quot;more&quot; than the Fourteenth Amendment requires.  If local employment or benefits are distributed on a racial basis to the benefit of racial minorities, the State apparently may not thereafter ever intervene.  Indeed, under the Court's theory one must wonder whether-under the equal protection component of the Fifth Amendment-even the Federal Government could assert its superior authority to regulate in these areas.</FONT><SUP><FONT FACE="Roman">8</P></SUP></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P><FONT SIZE=3>Significantly, the Court itself <I>denied</I> that its ruling had these implications. In a direct reply to the above passage, the <I>Seattle</I> Court said:</P>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<P><A NAME="footnote_23_at_480">Fn. 23 at 480:</A> Throughout his dissent, Justice POWELL insists that the Court has created a &quot;vested constitutional right to local decisionmaking,&quot; ... that under our holding &quot;the people of the State of Washington apparently are forever barred from developing a different <I>policy</I> [emphasis added] on mandatory busing where a school district previously has adopted one of its own,&quot; ... and that today's decision somehow raises doubts about &quot;the authority of a State to abolish school boards altogether.&quot;  ... These statements evidence a basic misunderstanding of our decision<I>.  Our analysis vests no rights</I> [emphasis added], and has nothing to do with whether school board action predates that taken by the State.  Instead, what we find objectionable about Initiative 350 is the comparative burden it imposes on minority participation in the political process-that is, the racial nature of the way in which it structures the <I>process</I> [emphasis in original] of decisionmaking.  It is evident, then, that the horribles paraded by the dissent ... --which have nothing to do with the ability of minorities to participate in the process of self-government-are entirely unrelated to this case.  It is equally clear, as we have noted at several points in our opinion, that the State remains free to vest all decisionmaking power in state officials, or to remove authority from local school boards in a race-neutral manner.<SUP>9</SUP></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</P>
<P>There is no way to read this passage except as a statement that the people of a state are <I>not</I> forever barred from developing a different policy on mandatory busing where a school district previously has adopted such a policy; that a higher governmental authority <I>may</I> intervene to overturn an affirmative action plan that has been approved by the admissions committee of a law school; that a state <I>may</I> set policy in an area where a local governmental body arguably has done &quot;more&quot; than the Fourteenth Amendment requires; etc.  Whatever the <I>Seattle</I>ruling means, therefore, it cannot mean that the people of a state are barred from constitutionalizing a prohibition against discrimination and preferences on the basis of race, sex, or ethnicity, as the people of California did when they adopted Proposition 209.</P>
<P>&#9;As will be argued at some length in the following sections of this paper, the key to interpreting <I>Seattle </I>is simply the distinction between (1) using a political decisionmaking process (such as a statewide ballot procedure) to adopt a policy bearing on a racial matter at a higher level of government, and (2) explicitly altering a decisionmaking process in a way that places a special burden on minorities on a specifically racial question.  It is the contention of this paper that the only possible way to interpret the Court's ruling in <I>Seattle</I> is to construe it as upholding the constitutionality of measures that fit the description in (1) above, even when the policy that has been adopted at a higher level of government makes it more difficult for minorities to obtain legislation that the Court might deem to be in their interest.  </P>
<P>It is evident that there must be a distinction between (1) and (2) above, for if the phrase &quot;alters the political decisionmaking process&quot; is to have any clear meaning, it cannot mean that a decisionmaking process is altered any time a policy is adopted at a higher level of government that precludes contrary policies at lower levels of government.  And if this is not what the phrase can mean generally, it cannot be taken to be the meaning of the phrase in the Court's <I>Seattle</I> decision. </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">THE <I>HUNTER</I> AND <I>REITMAN</I> PRECEDENTS</P>
</B><P>Two earlier Court cases, <I>Reitman v. Mulkey</I> (1967) and <I>Hunter v. Erickson</I> (1969), illuminate the Court's hostility to explicit alterations of the political decisionmaking process on specifically racial questions.</P>
<P>&#9;In 1964, the city council in Akron, Ohio enacted a fair housing ordinance and established a Commission on Equal Opportunity in Housing to enforce its provisions.  Subsequently, the Akron electorate amended the city charter by a citywide ballot initiative as follows:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>A.C.C. 137:&#9;</FONT><FONT FACE="Roman" SIZE=3>Any ordinance enacted by the Council of The City of Akron which regulates the use, sale, advertisement, transfer, listing assignment, lease, sublease or financing of real property of any kind or of any interest therein on the basis of race, color, religion, national origin or ancestry must first be approved by a majority of the electors voting on the question at a regular or general election before said ordinance shall be effective.  Any such ordinance in effect at the time of the adoption of this section shall cease to be effective until approved by the electors as provided herein.</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>The Akron city charter amendment essentially did two things. First, it repealed any housing ordinance regulating real estate transactions in the city on the basis of race and other factors that had previously been enacted by the city council.  Secondly, it required any future housing ordinance bearing on a racial question to be ratified by a majority of the city's voters in a general election.</P>
<P>It is important to note that Akron City Charter  137 did not establish a <I>right</I> to discriminate on the basis of race and other factors in private real estate transactions in the city of Akron.  Furthermore, in the campaign for the city charter amendment, and when defending the amendment in court, the measure's proponents and the city of Akron never said that they favored a policy establishing a right to discriminate in private real estate transactions.  They defended the measure instead on the grounds that any measure on this question was important enough to be submitted to the citywide electorate.<SUP>10</SUP> If the citizens of Akron <I>had</I> wanted to adopt a policy establishing a right to discriminate, moreover, they would have been barred from doing so by the Court's 1969 decision in <I>Reitman v. Mulkey</I>, where the Court struck down Proposition 14, a constitutional amendment which the people of the State of California had adopted in 1964.  This amendment provided in relevant part:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>Prop. 14: Neither the State nor any subdivision or agency thereof shall deny, limit or abridge, directly or indirectly, the right of any person, who is willing or desires to sell, lease or rent any part or all of his real property, to decline to sell, lease or rent such property to such person or persons as he, in his absolute discretion, chooses.</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>&#9;It is clear from the Fourteenth Amendment that a state cannot discriminate on the basis of race in its own real estate or any other transactions.  The question presented in <I>Reitman</I>, however, was the question whether the people of a state could constitutionalize a right to discriminate on the basis of race in <I>private</I> real estate transactions.  The <I>Reitman</I> Court held, 5 to 4, that Proposition 14 went beyond a position of neutrality with regard to private discriminations, and that by establishing a state right to privately discriminate it &quot;encouraged&quot; and &quot;authorized&quot; private discrimination.  The Court held that this involved the state in racial discrimination and hence was invalid under the Fourteenth Amendment.</P>
<P>If the people of the city of Akron <I>had</I> wanted to reserve to themselves the right to discriminate on the basis of race in private real estate transactions, therefore, the way would have been barred by the Court's prior ruling in <I>Reitman</I>. What the voters of Akron did instead was to strike down the city council's prior fair housing ordinances, and then to require in addition that all future housing ordinances bearing on race and certain other factors be submitted to a citywide referendum.  But even this measure was struck down by the Court, on the grounds that it singled out racial matters for special treatment and altered the political decisionmaking process in a way that placed special burdens on minority interests.</P>
<P>Note that the Court did not hold in <I>Hunter</I> that any policy bearing on a racial question that makes it more difficult for minorities to obtain legislation that is arguably in their interest is unconstitutional.  <I>Hunter </I>could not present this question, since the Akron city charter amendment repealed a fair housing ordinance, and the Court had already held in <I>Reitman </I>that laws establishing a <I>right</I> to discriminate in private transactions are unconstitutional.<SUP>11</P>
</SUP><P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><I><P ALIGN="CENTER">SEATTLE</I> IN THE LIGHT OF THE <I>HUNTER</I> AND <I>REITMAN</I> PRECEDENTS</P>
</B><P>The Court's opinion in <I>Seattle </I>rests squarely on its prior ruling in <I>Hunter</I>.  The analysis has the following form: (1) Initiative 350 is like Akron City Charter  137 in all constitutionally relevant respects; (2) the <I>Hunter </I>Court held Akron City Charter  137 unconstitutional; therefore (3) Initiative 350 is unconstitutional.<SUP>12</SUP>  To understand <I>Seattle</I>, therefore, it is essential to understand why the Court felt that Initiative 350 presented exactly the same constitutional issue that the Akron city charter amendment had presented to the <I>Hunter </I>Court.</P>
<P> Without taking a position on racial discrimination in private real estate transactions (Akron City Charter  137), or the merits of mandatory racial busing (Initiative 350), the electorate in these two ballot measures had explicitly altered the established political decisionmaking structure and placed decisionmaking power over a racial issue at a higher level of government.  Both measures were deemed by the Court to be violative of the Fourteenth Amendment.  But the Court did not say in either case-and in <I>Seattle</I> explicitly denied-that states have no power to establish a <I>policy</I> on a racial question that makes it more difficult for minorities to obtain legislation the Court might deem to be in their interest.  We have also seen that there are a priori reasons for <I>not </I>interpreting the phrase &quot;alters the political decisionmaking structure&quot; so broadly that it covers policies, adopted at a higher level of government, which make it more difficult for certain individuals or groups to obtain legislation at lower levels of government that is arguably in their interest.</P>
<P>&#9;The following principle HD summarizes these findings about the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>HD: A measure that addresses a racial question, and which explicitly and directly alters the political decisionmaking structure on that question in a way that places special burdens on racial minorities, offends the Fourteenth Amendment. Measures that offend the Fourteenth Amendment in this way include, but are not necessarily limited to, explicit alterations in the political decisionmaking structure that place decisionmaking authority over a specifically racial question at a higher and more remote level of government.</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>The following principle HD&#180; states what the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine does <I>not</I>prohibit:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P> HD&#180;:&#9;A policy measure that is adopted at a higher level of government through the use of an existing decisionmaking structure does not violate the Fourteenth Amendment, even if such a measure make its more difficult for minorities to obtain legislation that the Court might deem to be in their interest (provided, of course, that the measure itself is constitutionally permissible in all other respects).  When a higher level of government adopts such a measure, it is not altering the political decisionmaking structure in a way that violates the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine, but is simply exerting the power which it inherently has to establish any policies, including those bearing on specifically racial questions, that are not prohibited by the federal constitution.</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>Much if not most of the controversy between the Court and the minority justices in <I>Seattle</I> was on the question whether Initiative 350 violated the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine.  Justice Blackmun, writing for the Court, said that it did; Justice Powell, writing for the minority, said that it didn't.  On this particular point, Blackmun was clearly right, and Powell was clearly wrong.  The Court had no difficulty in showing, for example, that in Washington State decisionmaking authority over racial busing had generally been placed, at least as a matter of practice, in local school boards before the adoption of Initiative 350.  Given this well-established fact, it is obvious from inspection that Initiative 350 violated the <I>Hunter</I>doctrine as formulated in HD above, for it explicitly denied to local school boards decisionmaking authority over a racial question which school boards had previously held.  It was also a <I>non sequitur</I> for Justice Powell to suggest that the Court's holding in <I>Seattle</I> entailed that henceforth no state would be allowed to develop &quot;a different policy on mandatory busing where a school district previously has adopted one of its own,&quot; for Initiative 350 did not establish a policy on racial busing, nor did the Court's analysis imply that it had.</P>
<P>Since Initiative 350 possessed the very features which the <I>Hunter </I>Court had declared unconstitutional in the Akron city charter amendment, the minority justices in <I>Seattle</I> either had to join with the majority in striking down Initiative 350, or they had to qualify the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine, as formulated in HD above.  As it turns out, they did neither--hence the weakness of Powell's dissent.</P>
<P>Nevertheless, it is one thing to claim that Initiative 350 altered the political decisionmaking process on a racial question in the same way that Akron City Charter  137 had done, and quite another to hold that Initiative 350 was unconstitutional on those grounds.  What may well have been haunting the Court in <I>Hunter</I> was the fear that with City Charter  137 the citizens of Akron had achieved by indirect means what the people of the state of California had tried to achieve with Proposition 14.  This would be a legitimate concern for the Court, for the Court had already held Proposition 14 unconstitutional in <I>Reitman</I>.  But the situation was quite different in <I>Seattle</I>, for the Court had never held (and has not held since) that a prohibition against racial busing for the purposes of remedying<I> de facto</I> segregation is per se a violation of the federal constitution.  This suggests that HD may be overbroad, and that what the Court should have done in the face of Initiative 350 is to qualify and reformulate it.</P>
<P>One possibility might be to amend HD to permit explicit alterations of the political decisionmaking structure on a racial question if, but only if, in addition to repealing existing legislation on a racial question, the higher governmental authority could have prohibited all <I>future</I> measures similar to the ones that it repealed.</P>
<P>But there are problems even with this amended rule.  Suppose, for example, that the people of the state of Washington had passed a ballot measure that removed authority to order racial busing from local school boards, and in addition imposed a supermajority requirement for the enactment of mandatory racial busing measures, whether by the state legislature or by statewide initiative.  Such a measure would satisfy the suggested amended rule (because a policy prohibiting racial busing is not itself unconstitutional), but would clearly have been struck down by the <I>Seattle </I>Court, for it is one thing to grant a higher level of government--and only that level of government--decisionmaking authority on a racial question, and quite another to do that and <I>also</I> to place a supermajority requirement on the enactment of future legislation bearing on that question.  That is precisely the kind of alteration of the political decisionmaking process that the Court regarded as unconstitutional in <I>Hunter</I>.<SUP>13</P>
</SUP><P>&#9;Consequently, the amended rule would require further refinement.  But in any case it does not require refinement in order to bar Initiative 350, for that measure was innocuous in this respect: it did place decisionmaking authority over a racial matter at a higher level of government, but racial busing as a cure for <I>de facto </I>segregation is not required by the federal constitution, and the measure did not otherwise explicitly alter the political decisionmaking process.  Indeed, Initiative 350 was less far-reaching than a <I>policy</I> prohibiting mandatory racial busing would have been, for it left decisionmaking authority over such busing to the state legislature and to future ballot initiatives.  Nevertheless, the <I>Seattle</I> Court struck down Initiative 350, while its dicta in footnote 23 at 480 acknowledge that a policy prohibiting non-federally-required racial busing <I>would</I> have been constitutional.  While this is not an untenable result, it is an odd one.  It certainly suggests that it would have been in order for the Court to consider modifications of the doctrine enunciated in <I>Hunter </I>in order to avoid such paradoxical consequences.</P>
<P>The minority chose to argue instead that Initiative 350 did not violate the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine--a manifestly untenable claim.  The result was that the Court held, in effect, that even a measure like Initiative 350 <I>must conform to the strict letter of HD without qualification</I>--even though in its own opinion the <I>Seattle</I> Court declared that a measure embodying the policy choice which Initiative 350 simply left to the discretion of  the state legislature (i.e., a ban on racial busing to remedy <I>de facto</I> segregation) <I>would</I> have been constitutional had the electorate adopted that measure instead.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A NAME="amarcaminker_start">AMAR AND CAMINKER ON <I>WASHINGTON v.</I> <I>SEATTLE SCHOOL DISTRICT NO. 1</A></P>
</B></I><P>For the reasons given, Initiative 350 did not present the Court with a policy enactment by a higher level of government that made it more difficult for racial minorities to obtain race-conscious legislation at lower levels of government that the Court might deem to be in their interest.  Nevertheless, Amar and Caminker have argued that <I>Seattle</I> stands for the proposition that a measure like Proposition 209 is unconstitutional.<SUP>14</SUP>  Quite unaccountably, however, they never once mention that in footnote 23 at 480 the <I>Seattle </I>Court specifically <I>denied</I> that its ruling precluded a state from adopting a different policy on mandatory busing where a school district previously had adopted one of its own.</P>
<P>Amar and Caminker do cite part of the crucial footnote 23 at 480, as follows:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<P>...<I>see also Seattle</I>, 458 U.S. at 480 n. 23 (&quot;[T]he State remains free to vest all decisionmaking power in state officials, or to remove authority from local school boards in a race-neutral manner. . . . [W]hat we find objectionable about Initiative 350 is the <I>comparative</I> burden it imposes on minority participation in the political process . . . .&quot;) (emphasis added).<SUP>15</SUP></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</p>
<P>This partial citation of footnote 23 omits to mention that the footnote explicitly denies that the Court has created a &quot;vested constitutional right to local decisionmaking,&quot; or that it means that &quot;the people of the State of Washington apparently are forever barred from developing a different policy on mandatory busing where a school district previously has adopted one of its own.&quot;  Since Amar and Caminker never cite this part of the footnote, they never explicitly address the problem that such statements present to their interpretation of <I>Seattle</I>.  But the burden of their argument and partial citation of footnote 23 is clear enough.  On their view, the fact that the people of a state can adopt a different policy on mandatory busing where a school district previously has acted first means that they may do so <I>if and only if </I>they develop a policy on every <I>other</I> matter involving school transportation and school assignments, whether racial or non-racial.</P>
<P>Their interpretation is untenable, for several reasons.</P>
<P>First, as a purely textual point, the authors have reversed the order of the two sentences which they do cite from the footnote, and have omitted the qualifying phrase &quot;It is equally clear that...&quot; from the concluding sentence of the footnote.  That sentence reads in full:  &quot;It is equally clear, as we have noted at several points in our opinion, that the State remains free to vest all decisionmaking power in state officials, or to remove authority from local school boards in a race-neutral manner.&quot;<SUP>16</SUP> This qualifying phrase clearly implies that the points that follow cannot be regarded as providing the rationale for the statement that a state is permitted to adopt a policy on mandatory busing where a local school board has acted first.  In view of the qualification, the last sentence of the footnote can only be read as raising points that are separate from, and additional to, the points raised earlier in the footnote.</P>
<P>Second, the partial citation of footnote 23 by Amar and Caminker gives only the first half of the sentence that begins, &quot;Instead, what we find objectionable about Initiative 350 is the comparative burden it imposes on minority participation in the political process....&quot;  The second half of the sentence, which is omitted, says: &quot;that is, the racial nature of the way in which it structures the <I>process</I> of decisionmaking.&quot;  As it does elsewhere, the Court in this passage stresses the fact that Initiative 350 explicitly and on its face altered the political decisionmaking process.  This repeated emphasis cuts against the Amar-Caminker interpretation of <I>Seattle</I>, for according to their interpretation, this feature of Initiative 350 was ultimately of no importance to the Court.</P>
<P>Third, as a purely linguistic matter, theirs is simply not a natural or plausible reading of the statements in question.  If X is asked if Y has the authority to adopt a policy on a particular subject-matter, and the reply is that Y does have this authority, it is unnatural to interpret that affirmative answer to mean that Y may do so <I>if but only if</I> Y also reserves to himself decisionmaking authority on all <I>other</I> matters.</P>
<P>Fourth, the interpretation could be taken seriously only if the condition that it lays down could be met in the real world--and it obviously couldn't be.  While it might be possible for the people of a state to adopt a statewide measure that deals with the full range of policy choices that might arise in a very restricted domain, they clearly could not do so for a very broad range of governmental action.</P>
<P>Take, for example, the three very broad areas of governmental action covered by Proposition 209: public employment, public education, and public contracting.  According to the Amar-Caminker interpretation of <I>Seattle</I>, the only reason why the people of the State of California are not barred from constitutionalizing a prohibition against racial preferences in all three of these areas of governmental action is that the people of the state are not barred from taking <I>all</I> matters into their hands in these areas.  But it is ludicrous to imply, as this constitutional doctrine does, that the people of California could run all the affairs of the state (or at least withdraw all legislative and policy-setting authority at every level of state government to themselves) through the constitutional amendment process.  To take only one of the three areas covered by Proposition 209 as an example: the people of a state could not, as a practical matter, decide in their constitution all questions about overtime, compensation, pension plans, occupational safety standards and all other matters involving public employment.<SUP>17</SUP>  And if the Amar-Caminker interpretation of <I>Seattle</I> is untenable when applied to a state constitution, it must be rejected for all levels of government, for if it fails to provide an interpretation of <I>Seattle</I> when that precedent is applied to a state constitution, it fails to provide an interpretation of <A NAME="amarcaminker_end">footnote 23 of the <I>Seattle </I>opinion that is of general applicability</A>.<SUP>18</P>
</SUP><P>Although their implicit analysis of footnote 23 at 480 is clearly inadequate, Amar and Caminker do acknowledge that drawing a distinction between using an existing political decisionmaking process to enact a policy change on a racial matter at the highest level of government, on the one hand, and explicitly altering that decisionmaking process on the other, offers an initially plausible, prima facie basis for interpreting <I>Seattle</I>.<SUP>19</SUP>  They contend, however, that there is evidence within the <I>Seattle</I> opinion that the Court regarded the substance/procedure distinction as vague and unimportant constitutionally.  But the passage they cite in support of this assertion, which is given below, is not on point:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>Justice POWELL finds <I>Hunter</I> completely irrelevant, dismissing it with the conclusory statement that &quot;the political system has <I>not</I> been redrawn or altered.&quot;  <I>Post</I>, at 497-498.  The evil condemned by the <I>Hunter</I> Court was not the particular political obstacle of mandatory referenda imposed by the Akron charter amendment; it was, rather, the comparative structural burden placed on the political achievement of minority interests.  Thus, in <I>Hunter</I>, the procedures for enacting racial legislation were modified in such a way as to place effective control in the hands of the citywide electorate.  Similarly here, the power to enact racial legislation has been reallocated.  In each case, the effect of the challenged action was to redraw decisionmaking authority over racial matters-and only over racial matters-in such a way as to place comparative burdens on minorities.  While Justice POWELL and the United States find it crucial that the proponents of integrated schools remain free to use Washington's initiative system to further their ends, that was true in <I>Hunter</I> as well: proponents of open housing were not barred from invoking Akron's initiative procedures to repeal the charter amendment, or to enact fair housing legislation of their own.  It is surely an excessive formal exercise, then, to argue that the procedural revisions at issue in <I>Hunter</I> imposed special burdens on minorities, but that the selective allocation of decisionmaking authority worked by Initiative 350 does not erect comparable political obstacles.  Indeed, <I>Hunter</I> would have been virtually identical to this case had the Akron city charter amendment simply barred the City Council from passing any fair housing ordinance, as Initiative 350 forbids the use of all mandatory desegregation strategies.  Surely, however, <I>Hunter</I> would not have come out the other way had the charter amendment made <I>no</I> provision for the passage of fair housing legislation, instead of subjecting such legislation to ratification by referendum.<SUP>20</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

</SUP><P>It is hard to understand why Amar and Caminker regard this passage as evidence that the <I>Seattle</I> Court regarded the &quot;substance/procedure&quot; distinction as unimportant constitutionally.  On the contrary, the point of the passage is to show, <I>contra</I> Justice Powell, that Initiative 350 was in all constitutionally relevant respects exactly like Akron City Charter  137--and as we have seen, neither Initiative 350 nor the Akron city charter amendment was a policy enactment.</P>
<P>&#9;The passage is a direct response to Powell's allegation (1) that &quot;Nothing in <I>Hunter</I> supports the Court's extraordinary invasion into the State's distribution of authority;&quot; (2) that &quot;In this case, unlike in <I>Hunter</I>, the political system has not been redrawn or altered;&quot; and (3) that &quot;<I>Hunter</I>, therefore, is simply irrelevant.&quot;<SUP>21</SUP>  Blackmun has no difficulty showing that these claims are mistaken.  He begins by pointing out that Initiative 350 worked its changes precisely by altering the then-existing political decisionmaking structure.  Before the adoption of Initiative 350, decisions about racial busing were made by local schoolboards in Washington State; after the adoption of Initiative 350, only the state legislature and the people of the State of Washington had this power.  Likewise, in <I>Hunter, </I>he says, &quot;the procedures for enacting racial legislation were modified in such a way as to place effective control in the hands of the citywide electorate.&quot;  The effect in each case, he adds, is to &quot;redraw decisionmaking authority over racial matters.&quot;</P>
<P>&#9;In addition, Blackmun has no difficulty dispensing with Powell's claim that Initiative 350 differed constitutionally from Akron City Charter  137 on the grounds that proponents of mandatory racial busing in Washington State could use the initiative process to overturn Initiative 350 and obtain race-conscious legislation they deemed to be in their interest even after its adoption.  Blackmun replied that this did not distinguish Initiative 350 from the Akron city charter amendment, because the same was true of minority citizens seeking fair housing legislation after the adoption of Akron City Charter  137.</P>
<P>Indeed, if one ignores the fact (as Blackmun did in the above passage) that Initiative 350 left the <I>state</I> <I>legislature </I>free to order mandatory racial busing, and focuses solely on Initiative 350's effect on local school boards, the burden that Initiative 350 placed on the interests of minorities in Washington State was actually <I>greater</I> than the burden the Akron city charter amendment had placed on the interests of minorities in the city of Akron.  That is because Akron City Charter  137 established a two-step decisionmaking structure on housing ordinances involving racial issues.  It left the city council with the power to draft and propose housing ordinances involving racial questions, but left decisionmaking authority over such measures with the citywide electorate, which either adopted them or rejected them by majority vote.  (Alternatively, citizens could place such measures on the citywide ballot directly by gathering petition signatures from 10 percent of the citywide electorate.)  To get an exact analogy between the Akron city charter provision and Initiative 350, therefore, one would have to suppose that Akron City Charter  137 had removed even the drafting and proposing powers from the city council, just as, the Court argued, Initiative 350 had completely removed <I>all</I> power over racial busing from the local school boards.  But as Blackmun pointed out, this would have made Akron City Charter  137 even more vulnerable to attack under the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine, for that would have left the city council with <I>no</I> authority over such matters.</P>
<P>&#9;Since neither Initiative 350 nor Akron City Charter  137 involved a policy enactment on a racial question, the passage cited by Amar and Caminker cannot be taken as undermining the &quot;substance/procedure&quot; distinction-all the more so, since the Court explicitly <I>denied</I> that its ruling in <I>Seattle</I> barred such policy enactments in footnote 23 at 480.  The above passage is limited to arguing (quite correctly) that no matter how it is viewed, Initiative 350 is exactly like Akron City Charter  137 in all the respects that matter under the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><I><P ALIGN="CENTER">CrawforD v. Board of Education</I> (1982), 458 U.S. 527</P>
</B><P>There are additional reasons for rejecting the Amar-Caminker interpretation of the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine in an opinion that the <I>Seattle </I>Court delivered on the same day, <I>Crawford v. Board of Education</I> (1982), 458 U.S. 527.</P>
<P>Prior to Proposition I, a statewide constitutional amendment by initiative that was adopted by the California electorate in 1970, California courts had interpreted the equal protection clause of the California constitution to require the state to remedy <I>de facto</I> as well as <I>de jure</I> segregation in its public schools.  State courts had accordingly ordered racial busing in some instances where they would have had no authority to do so under the federal constitution.</P>
<P>Proposition I added a lengthy proviso to Article I, Section 7(a) of the California state constitution to prohibit such court-ordered busing.  Following passage of Proposition I, this section of the state constitution now provides in relevant part:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>Prop. I: (a) [1]  A person may not be deprived of life, liberty, or property without due process of law or denied equal protection of the laws;<I> </I>[2]<I> provided, that nothing contained herein or elsewhere in this Constitution imposes upon the State of California or any public entity board, or official any obligations or responsibilities which exceed those imposed by the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th Amendment to the United States Constitution with respect to the use of pupil assignment or pupil transportation. </I> [3]<I> In enforcing this subdivision or any other provision of this Constitution, no court of this state may impose upon the State of California or any public entity, board or official an obligation or responsibility with respect to the use of pupil school assignment or pupil transportation, (1) except to remedy a specific violation by such party that would also constitute a violation of the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th Amendment to the United States Constitution, and (2) unless a federal court would be permitted under federal decisional law to impose that obligation or responsibility upon such party to remedy the specific violation of the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th Amendment of the United States Constitution.</P>
</I><P ALIGN="CENTER">* * *</P>
<P>[4]<I>  Nothing herein shall prohibit the governing board of a school district from voluntarily continuing or commencing a school integration plan after the effective date of this subdivision as amended.</I><SUP>22</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

</SUP><P>The Court upheld the constitutionality of Proposition I, 8 to 1.</P>
<P>If one looked only at [3] above, this might seem surprising, since [3] has exactly the same form as Initiative 350, which the Court struck down the same day in its <I>Seattle</I> decision--i.e., it says &quot;[N]o court of this state shall order...,&quot; just as Initiative 350 said, in effect, &quot;No local school board shall order...&quot; etc.  But [3] cannot be considered in isolation, for it is in fact a mere corollary of [2].  Before the adoption of Proposition I, state courts had interpreted the Equal Protection clause of the state constitution to require the State of California to take race-conscious measures that went beyond anything required by the federal constitution.  Proposition I repealed that interpretation of the state constitution, and thereby brought the California constitution into conformity with the federal constitution on this particular question in every respect.  Thus, state courts could not enforce non-federally-required racial busing after the adoption of Proposition I, because the corresponding right on which such court-ordered busing had been based had been repealed.</P>
<P>This is exactly the point made by Justices Blackmun and Brennan in their concurring opinion in <I>Crawford</I>:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>State courts do not create the rights they enforce; those rights originate elsewhere-in the state legislature, in the State's political subdivisions, or in the state constitution itself.  When one of those rights is repealed, and therefore is rendered unenforceable in the courts, that action hardly can be said to restructure the State's decisionmaking mechanism.  While the California electorate may have made it more difficult to achieve desegregation when it enacted Proposition I, to my mind it did so not by working a structural change in the political <I>process </I>so much as by simply repealing the right to invoke a judicial busing remedy....<SUP>23</SUP></P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>Understandably enough, Amar and Caminker regard <I>Crawford</I> as a potential threat to their interpretation of the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine.  They attempt to meet this threat by arguing that the <I>Crawford</I> Court regarded it as an <I>essential </I>aspect of Proposition I that it did not limit the discretion of lower levels of government in California to order racial busing, and that Proposition I was therefore a &quot;mere repeal.&quot;  If it had not been a mere repeal, they argue, the <I>Crawford</I> Court would presumably have struck it down:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>Superficially, <I>Crawford </I>seems to establish some limiting principle to the reach of the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine, one that might appear to save the CCRI because it, like Proposition I, is a constitutional amendment that is (arguably) packaged as a substantive policy change rather than an alteration of political process.   On closer examination, however, <I>Crawford </I>represents an unexceptional application of the &quot;mere repeal&quot; rule.  Proposition I simply worked a repeal, <I>by the enacting entity </I>[emphasis in the original], of a substantive constitutional norm favorable to racial minorities.  It did not, by word or effect, withdraw pre-existing or future political authority from lower levels of government.<SUP>24</SUP></P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>It is true that Proposition I explicitly leaves the power to order racial busing with local school boards (cf. clause [4] of the citation of Proposition I above), and it is also true that at several places in its opinion the <I>Crawford</I> Court refers to that particular feature of Proposition I.  But there is no passage in the <I>Crawford </I>opinion that says or implies that the Court regarded this as an <I>essential </I>aspect of Proposition I-i.e., one that no similar measure could omit and still be declared constitutional under the <I>Hunter</I>doctrine.</P>
<P>Not only is there no evidence that the <I>Crawford </I>Court regarded this aspect of Proposition I as essential to a determination of its constitutionality: there are, in addition, compelling affirmative reasons for thinking that the <I>Crawford </I>Court did <I>not </I>view the matter this way. There is, first of all, the fundamental fact that in footnote 23 at 480 of its <I>Seattle </I>opinion, the Court explicitly denied that the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine vested rights to decide racial questions in lower levels of government in the way that the Amar-Caminker interpretation requires.  As if in direct reference to the <I>Crawford</I> decision--and even direct anticipation of Proposition 209--the <I>Seattle</I> Court in that footnote expressly <I>denied</I> that the &quot;horribles&quot; paraded by Justice Powell had any relevance to its decision-including Justice Powell's allegation that as a result of the <I>Seattle </I>decision a state might not be able to <I>set policy</I> in an area where a local governmental body arguably has done &quot;more&quot; than the Fourteenth Amendment requires.  But there is an additional reason as well: the view that the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine immunizes race-conscious measures taken by lower levels of government from policy prohibitions at higher levels of government leads to absurd results.</P>
<P>&#9;According to the Amar-Caminker interpretation of the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine, a state can create a right on the part of its citizens to be free of court-ordered mandatory racial busing, but is barred from creating a right on the part of its citizens to be free of such busing when it is ordered by a local school board.  This constitutional doctrine, besides being inconsistent with both the logic of the Court's analysis in <I>Crawford</I> and the explicit language of the Court's <I>Seattle </I>opinion, is absurd on its face.</P>
<P>If this view were correct, then the Fourteenth Amendment would grant greater political rights to minorities than it grants to whites.  Astonishingly, Amar and Caminker do not shrink from this conclusion:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>A state constitution may be amended so as to repeal or modify pre-existing constitutional provisions, even those that have been interpreted in a manner favoring a racial minority.  But a state constitution may not be amended in a direction that disadvantages the racial minority if the effect of such amendment would be to withdraw pre-existing <I>local or state legislative authority</I> [emphasis added] in a manner that is &quot;racial in character.&quot;  ...</P>
<P>We acknowledge that, so understood, the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine<I> </I>has<I> what some might perceive as a far-reaching consequence</I>.<SUP>25</SUP> With respect to a given issue that is &quot;racial in character,&quot; a state constitution may either remain neutral or prescribe norms favorable to racial minorities (which can later be repealed).  But a state constitution can <I>never </I>entrench a substantive norm with respect to an issue that is &quot;racial in character&quot; in a direction that disadvantages a racial minority.  For example, a constitution can mandate affirmative action, but it can never selectively prohibit it and thus foreclose the possibility of minority success in more accessible political arenas.<SUP>26</SUP></P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>What this means in plain terms is that at the constitutional level of government the people of a state can prohibit preferences for whites, but cannot prohibit preferences for minorities-or to put this another way, that a state can prohibit discrimination against minorities, but cannot prohibit discrimination against whites.  Whites, accordingly, in order to defend themselves against racial discrimination by governmental entities, must be prepared to combat affirmative action preferences now and forever (or at least until the Fourteenth Amendment is repealed) at each and every level of state and local government.  Whites cannot save themselves from this unpleasant task-which we know from experience will subject them to shrill cries of &quot;racism&quot;-by working to amend their state constitution.  Minorities, on the other hand, labor under no such restriction of their political rights.</P>
<P>The asserted constitutional doctrine has particularly absurd consequences at the federal level, which is arguably even more remote from local racial politics than a state constitution.  As Justice John Paul Stevens pointed out in his concurring opinion in <I>Johnson v. Santa Clara Transportation Agency</I> (1987), prior to 1978 the Court construed the Civil Rights Act of 1964 as an absolute blanket prohibition against discrimination which neither required nor permitted discriminatory preferences for any group, minority or majority.<SUP>27</SUP>  No one in his or her right mind at the time could possibly have supposed that under this construction the U.S. Civil Rights Act violated the U.S. Constitution, or that a state constitutional provision which fully conformed with the U.S. Civil Rights Act as it was then interpreted was unconstitutional.  According to the Amar-Caminker interpretation of the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine, however, the Civil Rights Act in its original meaning and as it was interpreted by the Court prior to 1978 was arguably unconstitutional under the Fourteenth Amendment, and all state constitutional provisions at that time having the same effect were also unconstitutional.<SUP>28</P>
</SUP><P>&#9;Typically, legal opponents of Proposition 209 deny that they are committed to the view that minorities have a constitutional right to preferential treatment.  But the view that a state is permitted to prohibit racial discrimination against minorities but cannot prohibit racial preferences in their favor clearly entails preferential treatment for minorities <I>in some form or other</I>.  Under the Amar-Caminker interpretation of <I>Seattle </I>and <I>Crawford</I>, it turns out that this preferential treatment lies in the domain of political rights.</P>
<P>&#9;It is true that the <I>Hunter</I> Court said, &quot;The majority needs no protection against discrimination and if it did, a referendum might be bothersome but no more than that.&quot;<SUP>29</SUP>  But this cannot be read as an endorsement of a doctrine of special political rights for racial minorities.  In that passage, the Court was simply laying out the conditions under which an explicit alteration of the political decisionmaking process, like that of Akron City Charter  137, violates the Fourteenth Amendment; and it was making the common sense point that a measure of this sort cannot escape constitutional scrutiny simply on the grounds that it subjects &quot;Negroes and whites, Jews and Catholics...to the same requirements if there is housing discrimination against them which they wish to end.&quot;<SUP>30</SUP>  One certainly does not commit oneself to a constitutional doctrine of unequal political rights in favor of minorities simply by acknowledging that the relative numerical strength of various racial groups might be constitutionally relevant in scrutinizing explicit alterations in the political decisionmaking process on racial questions.</P>
<P>Furthermore, the foregoing passage from <I>Hunter </I>surely cannot be interpreted to mean that antidiscrimination laws are irrelevant to the majority.  The Fourteenth Amendment does not provide protection under the laws just for minorities: it provides <I>equal</I> protection under the laws for all citizens.  Similarly, the U.S. Civil Rights Act does not prohibit discrimination only against women and minorities: it prohibits discrimination against anyone on the basis of race or sex generally.</P>
<P>It is as preposterous to read a doctrine of unequal distribution of political rights into the Fourteenth Amendment as it is to read into it a doctrine of preferential treatment on the basis of race in any other respect.  Nor is there any reason to think that the present Court, which has taken an increasingly hostile view towards racial gerrymandering to promote equality of results in the political process for minorities, would find any merit in Amar and Caminker's constitutional analysis, according to which decisional law presently grants political rights to minorities under the Fourteenth Amendment that it does not grant to whites.<SUP>31</P>
</SUP><P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">SOME FINAL COMMENTS ON FOOTNOTE 23 AT 480 OF <I>SEATTLE</P>
</B></I><P>&#9;The Achilles heel of the <I>Seattle </I>line of attack against Proposition 209 is footnote 23 at 480 of the <I>Seattle </I>opinion, where the Court explicitly <I>denied</I> that the people of a state are &quot;forever barred from developing a different policy on mandatory busing where a school district previously has adopted one of its own&quot;; <I>denied</I> that its decision vests special rights in lower levels of government on racial questions; <I>denied </I>that a state is precluded from setting policy in an area where a local governmental body arguably has done &quot;more&quot; than the Fourteenth Amendment requires; etc.  Either this means what it says or it doesn't.  If it does mean what it says, then <I>Seattle</I> cannot provide a rationale for holding Proposition 209 unconstitutional-for Proposition 209 is a pure policy enactment, rather than an explicit alteration in the political decisionmaking structure.</P>
<P>Obviously, one cannot have a policy that precludes racial busing without <I>formulating</I> and <I>enacting</I> such a policy.  Merely repealing all existing ordinances and laws requiring or permitting mandatory racial busing is not a <I>policy</I>: it is an absence<I> </I>of a policy.  Consequently, in asserting that a state could have a policy that precluded mandatory racial busing, the <I>Seattle </I>Court was necessarily committed to the view that a state could do <I>more</I> than merely repeal existing mandatory busing policies.  And this means, in turn, that the <I>Seattle </I>Court was committed to the view that it would be constitutionally permissible for a state to have a policy which might read, for example, as follows: </P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>The state shall not bus any student to a school other than the school that is nearest or the next nearest his or her place of residence in order to promote racial balance in the public schools, except in those certain instances where such busing is required by the federal constitution.  For the purposes of this section, &quot;state&quot; shall include, but not be limited to, the state, the State Department of Education, any local school board etc.</P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>&#9;The attempt by Amar and Caminker to accommodate footnote 23 at 480 of the <I>Seattle</I> opinion doesn't even begin to adequately address the problem.  They conclude their paper with the following two sentences:  &quot;There are, of course, constitutional ways to disestablish affirmative action programs throughout California.  But under the present law of the land, the CCRI does not appear to be one of them.&quot;<SUP>32</SUP>  This is obviously inadequate to deal with the problem, for they fail to provide a single example of how a state could prohibit such measures without doing, in so many words, exactly what Proposition 209 does: i.e., <I>explicitly</I> prohibiting them.  In other words, unless they can spell out some other<I> </I>way in which a state can have a <I>policy</I> prohibiting race-conscious measures in its state constitution, one is compelled to read footnote 23 at 480 in the <I>Seattle </I>opinion as permitting policy enactments like Proposition 209.</P>
<P>Judge Thelton H. Henderson of the U.S. District Court of the Northern District in California has also failed to address this fundamental issue in his analysis of <I>Seattle</I>.  In his findings of fact, conclusions of law, and order re the preliminary injunction against Proposition 209 he issued on December 23, 1996, he says:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>Defendants submit that the <I>Seattle </I>and <I>Hunter </I>cases cannot be read to invalidate Proposition 209, because such a reading would necessarily lead to an absurd reordering of the relationship between states and subordinate local government units.  According to this argument, if the Court accepts plaintiffs' position, such a holding would, in effect, permit local governmental bodies to preempt state authority on any racial or gender issue, at least where the local entity has acted to confer a benefit on minorities or women.</P>
<P>In making this argument, defendants rely primarily on concerns expressed by Justice Powell in his dissenting opinion in <I>Seattle.</I> 458 U.S. at 494-95, 498, n. 14.  As the majority in that case pointed out, however, the difficult dilemma posed by Justice Powell was not presented by Initiative 350.  <I>Id.</I> At 480 n. 23.  Similarly, the dilemma posed by defendants does not follow from plaintiffs' equal protection claim in the instant case.  Nothing about plaintiffs' argument requires that the state of California be forever barred from addressing a race- or gender-conscious affirmative action program where a local authority has acted first.  The <I>Seattle-Hunter </I>doctrine merely regulates the <I>manner </I>of any state intervention, preventing the state from nonneutrally reordering the political process to burden the interests of minorities or women.  A state, for example, remains free to restructure the political process in a neutral manner, even where such a change indirectly burdens the political participation of women and minorities.  A state may also intercede where it can articulate a justification that survives equal protection scrutiny.  What a state may not do, according to the <I>Seattle-Hunter </I>doctrine, is single out an issue of special interest to minorities and women and require that such legislation run a unique political gauntlet.</P>
<P>Plaintiffs' argument does not require that, once supporters of race- and gender-conscious affirmative action have suceeded [sic] at the ballot box, their victory can never be undone.  Nothing in the Constitution requires that the political system guarantee victory to those who support affirmative action.  The body that enacts an affirmative action measure is free, of course, to repeal it. ... <I>See Crawford</I>, 458 U.S. at 539.  ....</P>
<P>Once those who support race- and gender-conscious affirmative action prevail at one level of government, however, the Equal Protection Clause will not tolerate an effort by the vanquished parties to alter the rules of the game-solely with respect to this single issue-so as to secure a reversal of fortunes.  Plaintiffs have borne their burden of showing that Proposition 209, by removing authority over race- and gender-conscious affirmative action to &quot;a new and remote&quot; level of government, has precisely such an effect.  Such a reordering of the political process is tantamount to vote dilution in the most literal sense: the relevant voting pool is effectively expanded until the prior victory is undone.  <I>Cf. Gomillion v. Lightfoot, </I>364 U.S. 339 (1960) (holding that a state may not impair the voting rights of minorities under the guise of reapportionment).  Where such a political restructuring is aimed at a subject of particular interest to minorities and women, it is particularly problematic, and the Equal Protection Clause demands that it be subjected to heightened judicial scrutiny.  &quot;A law declaring that in general it shall be more difficult for one group of citizens than for all others to seek aid from the government is itself a denial of equal protection in the most literal sense.&quot;  <I>Romer </I>v. <I>Evans</I>, 116 S. Ct. 1620, 1628 (1996).<SUP>33</SUP></P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>Like the last two sentences of the Amar-Caminker paper, this passage fails to show how the view that Proposition 209 is unconstitutional under <I>Seattle </I>can be reconciled with the <I>Seattle </I>Court's statement that a state may have a <I>policy</I> that precludes race-conscious measures, even when a lower level of government has enacted such measures.  This point may become clearer by inspecting some of the specific assertions in this passage:</P>
<P> &#9;1.&#9;&quot;<I>As the majority in that case pointed out, however, the difficult dilemma posed by Justice Powell was not presented by Initiative 350</I>.&quot;  This response is inadequate because it fails to say <I>why</I> the difficult dilemma posed by Justice Powell was not presented by Initiative 350.  The obvious explanation is that Initiative 350 did not do so because it <I>did not embody a policy</I>.  If, on the other hand, Judge Henderson has a different understanding of why the <I>Seattle</I> Court held that the &quot;difficult dilemma posed by Justice Powell was not presented by Initiative 350,&quot; he is obligated to say what that interpretation is.  He clearly has not done so in this passage, and so far as the present author knows, he has not done so elsewhere.</P>
<P>2.&#9;&quot;<I>Nothing about plaintiffs' argument requires that the state of California be forever barred from addressing a race- or gender-conscious affirmative action program where a local authority has acted first</I>.&quot;   If the phrase &quot;addressing a race- or gender-conscious affirmative action program&quot; means &quot;having a <I>policy</I> prohibiting race- or gender-conscious affirmative action,&quot; the statement cited concedes the point at issue.  If, on the other hand, the phrase &quot;addressing a race- or gender-conscious affirmative action program&quot; means only that a state may <I>repeal</I> a race- or gender-conscious affirmative action program where a local authority has acted first, it is unacceptable as an interpretation of <I>Seattle </I>footnote 23 at 480, for a mere repeal is obviously different from a statewide policy that precludes race-conscious measures.</P>
<P>3.&#9;&quot;<I>Plaintiffs' argument does not require that, once supporters of race- and gender-conscious affirmative action have suceeded </I>[sic] <I>at the ballot box, their victory can never be undone.  ... The body that enacts an affirmative action measure is free, of course, to repeal it...&quot;</I> Again, this reply is inadequate because the <I>Seattle </I>Court's statement in footnote 23 at 480 cannot be interpreted as limited to mere repeals.   Furthermore, the statement that<I> &quot;The body that enacts an affirmative action measure</I> [emphasis added] is free, of course to repeal it...&quot; must be rejected because it appears to imply that an affirmative action measure can be repealed <I>only </I>by the body that enacted it.  This is plainly inconsistent with Judge Henderson's own statement that &quot;A state may also <I>intercede</I> [emphasis added] where it can articulate a justification that survives equal protection scrutiny,&quot; for intercession surely includes repeals.  It is also inconsistent with numerous passages in the <I>Hunter</I> trilogy of cases.<SUP>34</P>
</SUP><P>4.&#9;&quot;<I>Once those who support race- and gender-conscious affirmative action prevail at one level of government, however, the Equal Protection Clause will not tolerate an effort by the vanquished parties to alter the rules of the game-solely with respect to this single issue-so as to secure a reversal of fortunes.</I>&quot;  If this sentence means that any statement of <I>policy</I> by a higher level of government that precludes minorities from obtaining legislation that is in their &quot;interest&quot; at lower levels of government is an alteration of the &quot;rules of the game,&quot; then it is impossible to see how this statement can be reconciled with the view that a state <I>could </I>have a policy prohibiting racial preferences where another governmental body has acted first.  As was pointed out above, the proposition that the people of a state may adopt a race-neutral policy in their state constitution only on the condition that they also adopt a policy on each and every other conceivable question is totally impracticable.  Since this condition could never be met by any state constitution in the real world, imposing this condition would effectively preclude all race-neutral state constitutional provisions.</P>
<P><A NAME="henderson_gender">5.&#9;&quot;<I>Where such a political restructuring is aimed at a subject of particular interest to minorities </I>and women [emphasis added]<I>, it is particularly problematic, and the Equal Protection Clause demands that it be subjected to heightened judicial scrutiny</I>.&quot; </P>
<P>This statement, by including women in the analysis, betrays a total misunderstanding of the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine.  According to that doctrine, the majority is barred by the Fourteenth Amendment from using its numerical superiority to alter the political decisionmaking process in a way that specially burdens minorities on a racial issue.  The concern underlying the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine is to protect the interest of minorities in the political process, where they are at a disadvantage in obtaining legislation that is arguably in their interest precisely because they are a minority.<SUP>35</SUP>  It makes no sense to apply the same doctrine to women, because women comprise a political majority.</P>
<P>Judge Henderson's application of the &quot;heightened scrutiny&quot; for gender classifications to Proposition 209 also ignores the constitutionally relevant distinction between (1) a measure that uses an existing decisionmaking process to enact a policy on a racial question at a higher level of government, and (2) a measure that explicitly alters an existing decisionmaking process on a racial question. For example, Judge Henderson rejects the view that Proposition 209 serves the important state interest of ending discrimination on the basis of race and gender in the following terms:</P><DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>
<DIR>

<P>While undoubtedly important, however, this state interest is a non-sequitor [sic] with respect to Proposition 209.  The Court fails to see how this purported interest is related to, much less justifies, the nonneutral reordering of the political process that is at issue in this case.  As <I>Seattle</I> and <I>Hunter </I>make clear, it is <I>not </I>[emphasis in original] Proposition 209's prohibition on affirmative action that raises equal protection concerns; rather, it is the reordering of the political process that triggers exacting judicial scrutiny.  Defendants have not identified any feature of the prior political process that was discriminatory, and thus their invocation of a state interest in eliminating discrimination cannot justify the nonneutral reordering of that process.<SUP>36</SUP></P></DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>
</DIR>

<P>&#9;This passage asserts that the <I>purpose</I> of Proposition 209 is to reorder the political process to make it more difficult for women to obtain legislation that Judge Henderson deems to be in their interest.   But this is mistaken.  Unlike Initiative 350 and Akron City Charter  137, Proposition 209 does not explicitly alter the political decisionmaking process at all.  Unlike Initiative 350 and Akron City Charter  137, it <I>does</I> establish a policy, i.e., one of prohibiting discrimination and preferences on the basis, <I>inter alia</I>, of sex.</P>
<P>Judge Henderson acknowledges in the foregoing passage that prohibiting racial and gender discrimination constitutes an important state interest, but he regards that as irrelevant to Proposition 209, since that interest fails to justify what he regards as the &quot;nonneutral reordering of the political process that is at issue in this case.&quot;  But of course that state interest isn't irrelevant to Proposition 209, because the only way that the <I>State of California</I> can have a policy of prohibiting discrimination and preferences on the basis of sex is for the State of California <I>itself</I> to enact a measure prohibiting such discrimination and preferences.  This is precisely what the people of the State of California did on November 5, 1996 when they adopted Proposition 209 as Article I, Section 31 of the state constitution.</P>
<P>&#9;Like Amar and Caminker, Judge Henderson wants to have it both ways.  On the one hand, he would like to accommodate the plain meaning of footnote 23 at 480 of the <I>Seattle </I>opinion, according to which a state may have <I>policies</I> that prohibit race-conscious measures that are not required by the federal constitution, even when they preempt race-conscious measures taken by lower levels of government that the Court might deem to be in their interest.  On the other hand, he wants to hold that, according to the <I>Seattle </I>precedent, a state cannot have such policies.  This is incoherent because it is logically inconsistent.  By arguing that Proposition 209's prohibition of <I>gender</I> discrimination and preferences is likely unconstitutional under the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine, Judge Henderson has only compounded the confusion, for the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine cannot sensibly be applied to women voters, because women comprise a political majority of both the electorate <A NAME="henderson_gender_end">and of actual voters.</A><SUP>37</P>
</SUP><P></A></P>
<B><P ALIGN="CENTER">CONCLUSION</P>
</B><P>&#9;According to the <I>Seattle </I>Court, a state may adopt a policy that precludes race-conscious measures that arguably benefit racial minorities, even though that policy preempts race-conscious legislation at lower levels of government.  What it may not do is explicitly alter the decisionmaking structure on a specifically racial question in a way that makes it more difficult for racial minorities to obtain legislation that the Court might deem to be in their interest.  Since Proposition 209 is a pure policy enactment, and does not explicitly alter the political decisionmaking process on a racial question, it does not offend the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine.</P>
<P>&#9;It would have been astonishing if the <I>Seattle </I>Court had come to any other conclusion.  To reach the conclusion that the federal constitution prohibits such policies and civil rights measures, the <I>Seattle </I>Court would have had to stretch the expression &quot;explicit alteration of a political decisionmaking structure&quot; to the point where it loses any clear, recognizable meaning.  Secondly, it would have had to commit itself to the preposterous constitutional doctrine (which Amar and Caminker actually find meritorious) that a state can have a per se rule prohibiting discrimination against minorities, but cannot have a per se rule prohibiting discrimination against whites.  Minorities, accordingly, would have political rights under the Fourteenth Amendment that the majority does not have.</P>
<P>&#9;Amar and Caminker assure us that even under their interpretation of <I>Seattle </I>there are &quot;constitutional ways to disestablish affirmative action programs throughout California.&quot;<SUP>38</SUP>  But they do not say what these methods are.  Their statement cannot merely mean that each and every program of racial preferences can be repealed, one by one, by the governmental entity that enacted it, for the majority might have to wait forever for that to happen, and even if it did, the end result would fall short of a statewide policy <I>prohibiting</I> racial preferences.  The problem, of course, is that the statement of the <I>Seattle </I>Court in footnote 23 at 480 can sensibly be read only as acknowledging that statewide policy measures preempting race-conscious measures taken by lower levels of government are not per se unconstitutional, and that reading totally undermines the Amar-Caminker interpretation of the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine.</P>
<P>Unless the legal opponents of Proposition 209 can find another, plausible<I> </I>way of interpreting this plain, straightforward statement, <I>Washington v. Seattle School District No. 1</I> cannot be regarded as a court precedent that stands in the way of a judicial determination that Proposition 209 is constitutional, and legal opponents of the measure will have to look elsewhere for a pretext for striking it down. </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<hr>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><b>NOTES</B></P>

<P><SUP>1</SUP>Like the Amar-Caminker paper, this one focuses on the issue of race.  It does, however, criticize Judge Thelton Henderson of the U.S. District Court of Northern California for holding that the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine can and should be extended to include the criterion of gender.  <I>Vide infra, </I>pp. <A HREF="#henderson_gender">*</A>-<A HREF="#henderson_gender_end">*</A>.</P>
<SUP><P>2</SUP> From Washington Laws, 1979, Chapter 4 [Initiative Measure No. 350] SCHOOL ATTENDANCE NEAREST RESIDENCE, AN ACT Relating to school attendance; creating new sections; adding new sections to chapter 223.  Laws of 1969 ex. sess. and a new chapter to Title 28A RCW; and providing penalties.</P>
<SUP><P>3</SUP> Ibid.</P>
<SUP><P>4</SUP> Cf. &quot;Those favoring the elimination of <I>de facto</I> school segregation now must seek relief <I>from the state legislature</I> [emphasis added], or from the statewide electorate.&quot;  458 U.S. 474 (<I>Seattle</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>5</SUP> Cf. &quot;In our view, Initiative 350 must fall because it does 'not attemp[t] to allocate governmental power on the basis of any general principle.' <I>Hunter v. Erickson</I>, 393 U.S., at 395, 89 S.Ct., at 563 (Harlan, J., concurring).  Instead, it uses the racial nature of an issue to define the governmental decisionmaking structure, and thus imposes substantial and unique burdens on racial minorities.&quot;  458 U.S. 470 (<I>Seattle</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>6</SUP> The provision read: &quot;It is the paramount duty of the state to make ample provision for the education of all children residing in its borders without distinction or preference on account of race, color, caste, or sex.&quot;  Justice Powell noted in his dissent that the Supreme Court of the State of Washington had not interpreted this provision to prohibit race-conscious school assignments in the absence of a violation of the Fourteenth Amendment.  But surely, Powell pointed out, one would suppose that the state court <I>could</I> have rendered such a decision without violating the federal constitution.</P>
<SUP><P>7</SUP> Citing  <I>Bakke</I>, 438 U.S. 265.  Cf. the following passage from the dissent by Brennan et al. in <I>Bakke</I>: &quot;It may be that the Harvard plan is more acceptable to the public than is the Davis 'quota.'  If it is, any State, including California, is free to adopt it in preference to a less acceptable alternative, just as it is generally free, as far as the Constitution is concerned, to abjure granting any racial preferences in its admissions program.&quot;  438 U.S. 379 (<I>Bakke</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>8</SUP> 458 U.S. 498, fn. 14 (<I>Seattle</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>9</SUP>  This is a full citation of the footnote.  Ellipses indicate merely the omission of internal references.</P>
<SUP><P>10</SUP> Cf. &quot;We are unimpressed with any of Akron's justifications for its discrimination.  Characterizing it simply as a public decision to move slowly in the delicate area of race relations emphasizes the impact and burden of  137, but does not justify it.&quot;  393 U.S. 392 (<I>Hunter</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>11</SUP> In <I>Reitman</I>, the Court held that while it would permissible for the people of a state to repeal all existing fair housing laws, the people of a state could not amend their constitution to establish a right to discriminate on the basis of race in private real estate transactions.  There is no constitutionally relevant point in common between the measure held unconstitutional in <I>Reitman</I> and Proposition 209, which contains a stronger prohibition against racial discrimination and preferences than anything that is presently found in either the federal constitution or the constitution of the State of California.  The ban against racial discrimination in Proposition 209 is a per se rule.  Existing state and federal bans against racial discrimination fall short of this.  Consequently, it cannot be argued that in going beyond a &quot;mere repeal&quot; of laws and measures permitting racial preferences, Proposition 209 runs afoul of the Court's ruling in <I>Reitman</I>.  For 209 to run afoul of that ruling, it would have to be shown that Proposition 209's per se ban against racial discrimination implicates the state in racial discrimination.  Such a claim would be absurd.</P>
<SUP><P>12</SUP> Cf. the following passages from <I>Seattle </I>which cite the <I>Hunter</I> precedent:  &quot;In the end, appellants are reduced to suggesting that <I>Hunter</I> has been effectively overruled by more recent decisions of this Court.&quot;  458 U.S. 484.  &quot;For present purposes, it is enough that minorities may consider busing for integration to be 'legislation that is in their interest'.... Given the racial focus of Initiative 350, this suffices to trigger application of the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine.&quot;  454 U.S. 474.  &quot;We are also satisfied that the practical effect of Initiative 350 is to work a reallocation of power of the kind condemned in <I>Hunter.</I>  ...  As in <I>Hunter</I>, then, the community's political mechanisms are modified to place effective decisionmaking authority over a racial issue at a different level of government.&quot;  458 U.S. 474.  &quot;Appellants' suggestion that this analysis somehow conflicts with <I>Hunter</I>, however, misapprehends the basis of the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine.&quot;  458 U.S. 485.</P>
<P>Cf. also 458 U.S. 470, which refers to both <I>Hunter</I> and <I>Lee</I> <I>v</I>. <I>Nyquist</I> (318 F. Supp. 710 (WDNY 1979)):  &quot;We believe that the Court of Appeals properly focused on <I>Hunter</I> and <I>Lee</I>, for we find the principle of those cases dispositive of the issue here.  In our view, Initiative 350 must fall because it does 'not attemp[t] to allocate governmental power on the basis of any general principle.' ... Instead, it uses the racial nature of an issue to define the governmental decisionmaking structure, and thus imposes substantial and unique burdens on racial minorities.&quot;</P>
<SUP><P>13</SUP> Cf. &quot;Certainly, a state requirement that 'desegregation or antidiscrimination laws,' ... and only such laws, be passed by unanimous vote of the legislature would be constitutionally suspect.  It would be equally questionable for a community to require that laws or ordinances 'designed to ameliorate race relations or to protect racial minorities' ... be confirmed by popular vote of the electorate as a whole, while comparable legislation is exempted from a similar procedure.&quot;  458 U.S. 486-487 (<I>Seattle</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>14</SUP> Cf. &quot;The CCRI singles out race and treats it differently from any other criterion for public employment, education, and contracting decisions. In doing so, the CCRI isolates an issue of special interest to minorities-affirmative action programs ... --and relegates this issue to the highest and most entrenched level of governmental decisionmaking.  This would seem to violate the Equal Protection Clause as interpreted by the Court in the <I>Hunter</I> trilogy [<I>Hunter v. Erickson; Washington v. Seattle School District No. 1</I>; and <I>Crawford v. Board of Education</I>].&quot;  Ibid., p. 3.</P>
<SUP><P>15</SUP> Ibid., p. 27, fn. 85.</P>
<SUP><P>16</SUP> The footnote is cited in full at p. <A HREF="#footnote_23_at_480">*</A>, <I>supra</I>.</P>
<SUP><P>17</SUP>Although it is an obvious logical point, it might be worth noting here that within any given domain the category &quot;racial or non-racial&quot; covers <I>everything</I>.</P>
<SUP><P>18</SUP> In fact, the Amar-Caminker interpretation of <I>Seattle</I> is not even plausible when it is applied to the state legislature and to state officials, for the idea that the people of California could designate the state legislature to be the sole policy-making body in the state is also absurd.  An arrangement of this sort would entail a degree of bureaucratic centralism in the governance of the state that was not even approached in the Soviet Union by the Politburo during the era of Josef Stalin.  A monolithic decisionmaking of the required sort would in all likelihood not be feasible, and in any case would certainly be undesirable, in a state the size of California.  But this suggestion is arguably slightly less absurd than the suggestion that the people could write all policies, for all levels of government in the state, into the state constitution through the initiative process.  That suggestion is <I>totally</I> absurd.</P>
<P>The difference between the interpretation of footnote 23 that is advocated in this paper and the one provided (elliptically and implicitly) by Amar and Caminker, can be summarized as follows.  On the interpretation that is advocated here, the assertion in footnote 23 that a state is permitted to adopt a policy prohibiting race-conscious action even when a local school board has acted first means exactly what it says.  According to Amar and Caminker, however, it means that the state government may do so, but only if it also accepts responsibility for setting policy on every <I>other </I>conceivable matter.  But their assertion that the people of a state may establish a race-neutral policy even when a subordinate jurisdiction has enacted a race-<I>conscious</I> policy first is at war with the claim that the people of a state may do so only if they reserve <I>all</I> policy-making responsibilities to themselves, for this condition could never be met in the real world.  There is therefore a contradiction.  Hence the Amar-Caminker interpretation of footnote 23-which is totally unnatural and implausible on its face anyway-is untenable.</P>
<P>Finally, let it be noted that the problem is not with the rule laid down in <I>Seattle</I> that an <I>explicit</I> alteration of the political decisionmaking structure on a specifically racial question that disadvantages racial minorities is unconstitutional.  According to that principle, any <I>explicit</I> change in the decisionmaking structure cannot be specifically directed to a racial question, but must apply generally.  That constitutional principle is workable, and does not lead to the  result that race-conscious measures by subordinate entities preempt race-neutral policies by higher governmental entities unless higher governmental entities are <I>also </I>prohibited from adopting race-neutral policies directly, quite independently of that constitutional principle.  It is the combination of <I>Seattle's </I>constitutional doctrine with the Amar-Caminker assertion that a pure policy enactment like Proposition 209 is <I>also </I>unconstitutional that leads inexorably to the conclusion that race-neutral policies by higher levels of government are preempted whenever race-conscious policies benefiting racial minorities have been adopted by subordinate levels of government.  This result is plainly irreconcilable with the <I>Seattle </I>Court's assertion in footnote 23 that a higher governmental entity is not forever barred from having such a policy when a subordinate entity has acted first.</P>
<SUP><P>19</SUP> Cf. &quot;Some might try to invoke a procedure-substance distinction in an effort to separate the CCRI from the initiatives found wanting in <I>Hunter</I> and <I>Seattle</I>.  In both of these cases, the Court's language repeatedly characterized the initiatives at issue as having 'restructured' the pre-existing political process to impose burdens that are 'racial in character.' ... This repeated emphasis at least raises the possibility that such <I>explicit </I>restructuring is conceived by the Court to be an integral part of the unconstitutional burden driving the <I>Hunter</I> doctrine.  In other words, one might argue, the <I>Hunter </I>doctrine prohibits states from enacting initiatives that <I>on their face</I> directly restructure the pre-existing political process in a manner that is 'racial in character,' but does not similarly prohibit states from enacting initiatives that on their face merely 'work a simple change in policy,' even if they <I>incidentally </I>entrench the new policy.</P>
<P>&quot;We acknowledge that such a purported procedure-substance distinction might at first blush provide a plausible defense of the CCRI.  After all, on its face the CCRI looks more like a mere change of policy rather than a direct attempt to reallocate political power within the state.  Unlike the Akron charter amendment and Initiative 350, the CCRI does not directly declare that it is withdrawing political authority from one government level and vesting it solely in a higher one (i.e., the constitutional amendment process).&quot;  Amar and Caminker, p. 28.</P>
<SUP><P>20</SUP> 458 U.S. 474, n. 17 (<I>Seattle</I>).  Cited in part by Amar and Caminker, ibid., p. 30, where the passage is adduced as evidence that the <I>Seattle </I>Court explicitly rejected a &quot;bright-line distinction between procedural and substantive changes&quot; (p. 29).  Although the authors opine that this rejection is &quot;consistent with the Court's general concern for real-world effects and its rejection of formalism,&quot; they fail to mention footnote 23 at 480 of the <I>Seattle </I>opinion in this connection.  As argued above (pp. <A HREF="#amarcaminker_start">*</A>-<A HREF="#amarcaminker_end">*</A>), there is no plausible way of interpreting that footnote except as an acknowledgment by the Court that this distinction <I>is</I> a constitutionally important one.</P>
<SUP><P>21</SUP><FONT FACE="Roman"> 458 U.S. 497; 458 U.S. 497-498; 458 U.S. 498 (<I>Seattle</I>).</P>
</FONT><SUP><P>22</SUP> In citing this section of the California state constitution, the square brackets &quot;[1]&quot;, &quot;[2]&quot;, &quot;[3]&quot;, and &quot;[4]&quot; have been inserted to facilitate references to particular phrases in the following exposition.  Before the adoption of Proposition I, Article I, Section 7(a) included only (a)[1]; (a)[2]-(a)[4] were added to it by Proposition I.  The latter portions have been italicized in the citation.</P>
<SUP><P>23</SUP> 458 U.S. 546 (<I>Crawford</I>).  The opinion was written by Justice Blackmun.</P>
<SUP><P>24</SUP> Amar and Caminker, pp. 31-32.</P>
<SUP><P>25 </SUP>Emphasis added.  This is an understatement: the consequence is not just far-reaching, it is preposterous.</P>
<SUP><P>26</SUP> Ibid., pp. 34-35.</P>
<SUP><P>27</SUP> <I>Johnson v. Transportation Agency, Santa Clara County, California, </I>et al., 480 U.S. 642-643 (1987) (concurring opinion, Justice Stevens).</P>
<SUP><P>28</SUP> Cf. &quot;Indeed, under the Court's theory one must wonder whether-under the equal protection component of the Fifth Amendment-even the Federal Government could assert its superior authority to regulate in these areas.&quot;  458 U.S. 498, fn. 14 (from Justice Powell's dissent).  Like all the other &quot;horribles&quot; paraded by Justice Powell in his dissent, this allegation was denied by the Court in footnote 23 at 480 of the <I>Seattle </I>opinion.  It is significant, in fact, that the Court majority did not credit <I>any</I> of Powell's allegations.  All were simply denied, outright.</P>
<SUP><P>29 </SUP>393 U.S. 391 (<I>Hunter</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>30</SUP> 393 U.S. 390 (<I>Hunter</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>31</SUP> See <I>Shaw v. Reno</I> (1993) 125 L Ed 2d 511, where the Court held that a particularly egregious instance of racial gerrymandering constituted a racial classification, and was therefore unconstitutional unless it could be justified as furthering a compelling state interest.</P>
<SUP><P>32</SUP> Ibid., p. 39.</P>
<SUP><P>33</SUP> Judge Thelton H. Henderson, Chief Judge, United States District Court for the Northern District of California, FINDINGS OF FACT, CONCLUSIONS OF LAW AND ORDER RE PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION, <I>Coalition for Economic Equity</I>, et al., v. <I>Pete Wilson</I>, et al., No. C 96-4024 THE, December 23, 1996, pp. 44-46.</P>
<SUP><P>34</SUP> Cf. the <I>Seattle </I>Court's explicit denial of Justice Powell's claim that under the Court's ruling no higher authority could &quot;intervene&quot; in a state law school's affirmative action policies unless that authority &quot;traditionally dictated admissions policies.&quot;  458 U.S. 480, fn. 23.  Also: &quot;Had Akron's fair housing ordinance been defeated at a referendum, for example, 'Negroes would undoubtedly [have lost] an important political battle, but they would not thereby [have been] denied equal protection.&quot; 458 U.S. 483 (<I>Seattle</I>).  Many other counterexamples could be cited to the view that race-conscious measures can be repealed only by the governmental body that enacts it. </P>
<SUP><P>35</SUP> Cf. &quot;...when the State's allocation of power places unusual burdens on the ability of racial groups to enact legislation specifically designed to overcome the 'special condition' of prejudice, the governmental action seriously 'curtail[s] the operation of those political processes ordinarily to be relied upon to protect minorities.'  <I>United States v. Carolene Products Co</I>., 304 U.S. 144, 153, n. 4, 58 S.Ct. 778, 783-784, n. 4, 82 L.Ed. 1234 (1938).  In a most direct sense, this implicates the judiciary's special role in safeguarding the interests of those groups that are 'relegated to such a position of political powerlessness as to command extraordinary protection from the majoritarian political process.'  <I>San Antonio Independent School Dist. v. Rodriquez</I>, 411 U.S. 1, 28, 93 S.Ct. 1278, 1296, 36 L.Ed.2d 16 (1973).&quot;  458 U.S. 486 (<I>Seattle</I>).</P>
<SUP><P>36</SUP> Ibid., p. 43.</P>
<SUP><P>37</SUP> As it turns out, the women voters of the state do not even agree with Judge Henderson that preferences on the basis of sex are in their interest-or, if they do believe that they are in their &quot;interest&quot; in some sense, they voted to abolish them anyway.  According to the Voter News Service's exit polling on November 5, 52 percent of those who voted on Proposition 209 were women.  Of these, 52 percent voted for the measure; 48 percent voted against it.  Of white women who voted on the measure, 59 percent voted for it; 41 percent voted against it.</P>
<SUP><P>38</SUP> Ibid., p. 43.</P>
<p>
