	<td colspan=2 align=right><b>- - Becky Norton Dunlop, Secretary of Natural Resources,<br>Commonwealth of Virginia
</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td colspan=2><i>Facts, Not Fear</i> helped me understand just how easily a child's mind can  be manipulated all in the name of consciousness-raising.  Thanks for showing me the way to ease the fears of my three boys as they take in the information they are constantly exposed to by well-meaning adults.<br></td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td colspan=2 align=right><b>- - Carole Walden, parent</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td colspan=2>"Finally somebody has produced a readable book on the environment based on sound scientific facts.  Facts, Not Fear is essential reading for parents and teachers who want children to learn the truth behind today's frightening headlines of ecological disaster."</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td colspan=2 align=right><b>- - John Fund, The Wall Street Journal</b></td>
</tr>


<tr>
	<td width=50% valign=top>Too much fear and too few facts have brought the environmental weight of the world on the shoulders of our children.  Elementary student, Catherine Mitchell, writes, "I'm also too young to die, I might add, so stop burning the Earth!"  The days of litterbug campaigns and aerosol can boycotts pale in the fact of a fast-paced environmental movement that predicts impending doom and disaster.</td>
	<td width=50% valign=top>Without a more balanced approach to environmental education, we may soon add childhood to the endangered species list.  Facts, Not Fear provides parents and teachers accurate information to address children's concerns about the health of our planet.  This book gives balanced attention to environmental issues that plague our generation.  It will show - - through non-technical everyday language, "Talking with Your Children" sections, and creative activities - - how you can set the environmental record straight.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td colspan=2><font size="+1"><b>In <i>Facts, Not Fear</i> You Will Find:</b></font><br>
	<ul>
	<li>A comprehensive review of 14 environmental issues such as recycling, global warming, acid rain, rain forests, pesticides, and endangered species.
	<li>Non-technical language that helps parents understand the complex science and economics on which many environmental issues are based.
	<li>Environmental facts that have been reviewed by a Scientific and Advisory Panel of 32 distinguished scientists.
	<li>"Talking to Your Children" sections that provide parents answers to their children's commonly asked environmental questions.
	<li>"Activities for Parents and Children" sections that give parents the opportunity to reinforce information in the book by engaging in "simple to do" activities with their children, such as visiting the local lumber yard or grocery store.</ul></td>

<tr>
	<td colspan=2><font size="+1"><b><i>Facts, Not Fear</i> will help you:</b></font><br>
	<ul>
	<li>Learn a simple way to explain the garbage crisis issue to your children.
	<li>Find out where school boards and legislators get their direction to infuse the environmental message into all grade levels nd subject matters.
	<li>See why every year we have more timber than the year before despite the harvesting of trees for paper and lumber.
	<li>Learn how better technology and competitive market forces continue to improve air quality.
	<li>See how scientists take the earth's temperature and what their studies indicate about global warning.
	<li>Get answers to questions such as:  do pesticides on our food cause cancer in humans?; what was wrong with DDT?; should we buy only organic foods?
	<li>Tackle the recycling issue:  What are we really getting in return for all of this effort?</ul></td>
</table>
<br><br><br>

<center><table width=90% cellpadding=5>
<tr>
	<td valign=top><img src="/images/sanera1.jpg" width=97 height=130 border=0 alt=" "></td>
	<td valign=top>Michael Sanera is the Director of the Center for Environmental Education Research, a division of The Claremont Institute.  For the past seventeen years, he taught political science and public administration at Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff.  He is a native of Arizona and lives in Tucson with his youngest son.</td>
	<td valign=top><img src="/images/shaw1.jpg" width=96 height=129 border=0 alt=" "></td>
	<td valign=top>Jane Shaw is a Senior Associate of PERC (Political Economy Research Center) where she directs an editorial outreach program.  PERC is a nonprofit institute that studies market approaches to environmental problems.  She lives with her family in Bozeman, Montana.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td colspan=2 valign=top>"Our book provides parents and teachers with practical advice and hands-on activities which can be used in the home or classroom.  Instead of eliciting fear of environmental gloom and doom from children, parents and teachers who use this book will spark natural curiosity and critical thinking in their children"<p align=right><i><b> - - Michael Sanera, co-author
</b></i></td>
	<td colspan=2 valign=top>"In writing Facts, Not Fear, we used our experience as parents to help other parents talk to their children about the serious environmental problems faced by this nation and the world.  Our book carries the message that while we face serious environmental problems, children must learn that they are not insoluble and that they should look to the future with hope."<p align=right><i><b> - - Jane S. Shaw, co-author
</b></i>

</table>
</center></center>
