<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>

<TITLE>NR Soapbox-weekend</TITLE>


<CENTER><img src="/nationalreview/images/soap2.gif" ALT="NR Soapbox"></center>

<!---------------------------------------------------------------->




The NR Soapbox is a place where <I>NR Online</I> readers can voice their opinions regarding the major issues of the day. Respond to the question directly, or comment on previous responses. 
The featured question will change at the end of each week; comments will be updated daily.
Please keep comments brief (100 words or fewer).<br>

<P>
We are no longer accepting responses on the subject of Israel, Netanyahu, and American policy.<p>
<center><H3>This week's question is:</H3></center>
<center><H1><I>Is Clinton's 1998 budget proposal a move toward fiscal responsibility?</I></H1></center>
<P> 
 <center><b>To submit your answer to next week's question</b>,</center><br> 
<center><A HREF="mailto:nronline@ix.netcom.com"><img src="/nationalreview/images/click.gif" ALT="Click Here"></a>.<br></center>
<P> 

<center><H3>This week's (now irrelevant) question:</H3><br>
<H2>Israel: Is Netanyahu, American Policy on the Right Track?</H2></center>

 <P>
<hr>
<P>
Updated  2/7/97 
<HR>
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------>

<P>
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------>
I agree with Karen. The real underlying problem is in the fact that the
complete elimination of Israel is the ultimate goal of the Arabs. Making
any concessions in such a situation is very unwise for Israel. Nearly all
parties involved prefer to pretend that the only problem is Israel's
control of some territories in Judea, Samaria and Gaza and that Arab
control of these territories would insure lasting peace. Quite the
opposite is true. In fact Israel gained control over these territories
in the course of war initiated by Arab countries with the purpose of the
total destruction of the Jewish state. So the territories (or their
inhabitants) have nothing to do with the issue (by the way, during two
decades of Jordanian control Palestinians on the west bank of Jordan
were not given any autonomy, moreover their political activities in that
direction were brutally suppressedironically, Israeli security forces
never came even close to that level of brutality against Palestinians). <br>
<I>-Andrew Pavelyev, http://www.cosm.sc.edu/~pavelyev/pavelyev.html</I>
<hr>
<hr>
2/5/97<br>
Ever since 1948 the Moslem nations in the middle east have been
determined to annihilate the Jews in Israel. One way or another this is
still their purpose. The only way that Israel will continue to be able
to exist in such a sea of hostility is to have a big stick ready to
thump anyone trying to harass them. This problem has been faced by
hundreds of nations over the centuries. Let's pray that America
continues to support Israel or else one day we might see another
holocaust. The Moslems should read their own Koran and be at peace with the Jews.<br>
<I>karen cheney, "karenc@povn.com"@povn.com</I>
<hr>
2/5/97<br>
The PM is not going to agree to any terms as long as Arabs are killing Jews. The former PM sold his countrymen down then river; more Jews have been killed during the so-called peace than during the previous ten years in America. We need to stand up for legitimate rightsI'm tired of always placating certain groups. It's time to take charge, which is what Israel and the USA resent.<br>
<I>Biker40951@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<hr>

2/4/97<br>
What American Policy? The Clinton government only follows a policy that the
polls dictate.<br>
<I>Dan Shaw, dshaw@nbserv2.dseg.ti.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
2/4/97<br>
Most recently, he seems to be drifting away from a hard-line policy, but if
he should resume catering to the extremist in his party alliances, Congress
should start reviewing funds allocation. He will soon continue talking of peace. 
Since the Arabs have little to bargain with, Israel must lead the way in peace negotiations. 
The longer the Palestinians experience peace, the less inclined they will be toward renewed
attacks on Israel.<br>
<I>JLang912@aol.com</I>
	
<hr>
<P>
2/4/97<br>
Mark, who do you think is not on the right track?  Do you think that
Netanyahu is placing any trust in Arafat?  Pulling his troops out of
Palestinian territory demonstrates no trust in Arafat.  Arafat is not to
be trusted and I don't think Netanyahu will make that mistake.  With
regards to U.S. policy towards Israel, Clinton fails  as he has failed
in all foreign policy.  As long as he regards advice from the likes of
Barbara Streisand as sage, or the diplomacy of Jimmy Carter as
indeipensable, then we will have to conclude it is Clinton that is on
the wrong track.  However we will have to dismiss his lousy foreign-
policy record as simply poor judgment until we find out how much
Iranian money contributed to his re-election. Iran has, after all,
had closer ties with the Soviets than Israel ever has, and Clinton has
demonstrated how easily U.S. policy can be bought.  If it weren't for the
Jewish wealth in this country, Clinton would have sold them down the
Jordan river already!<br>
<I> Dan Shaw, dshaw@nbserv2.dseg.ti.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
2/4/97<br>
Tend to agree with Ravitch on this one, but we must chart the course  
that preserves American leadership without being everyone's keeper. We  
should pay our fair share where people are willing to work/fight for  
democracy and economic prosperity. We do not need to get involved in the  
side issues that Israel and D'Amato keep pitching in the fire. Curious  
that Ms. Albright suddenly discovers her history in the related fray! <br>
<I>Bill</I>
<hr>
<hr>

2/3/97<br>
No. It seems as though the lesson will never be learned: surrender to and appeasement of aggression and terrorism only feeds the flames of such deplorable behavior. Why Arafat is seen as one with any control over his "principals," the Palestinians, and would thus be in a position to be taken seriously as a negotiator on their behalf is another question altogether. However, Netanyahu obviously takes a superior approach to negotiation when compared to his predecessors' desire to cede as much as possible for as little as possible in return.<br> 
<I>Mark G. Heiman, heiman@fas.harvard.edu</I>
<hr>
<P>
2/3/97<br>
Netanyahu's unwise attempt to essentially rewrite the agreements reached with Arafat by the previous Israeli government will ultimately redound to the detriment of the Israeli people. Unlike many of my brethren on the right, I am far from sanguine on chances of survival for the nation of Israel, and "in your face" arrogance from the right in Israel has always reminded me of the proverbial whistler walking by the graveyard. Israel relies on technological and tactical superiority to keep the Arabs at bay, as well as the strength of its most important ally, the United States. Parity between Arabs and Israelis in technology and military sophistication is not far off. After this event arrives, as it surely will, how then will the United States keep 140 million Arabs from working their will in their ancestral homeland against a few million Israelis?<br> 
<I>Worth Colliton, becket20@aol.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
2/3/97<br>

It is about time that American policy towards Israel became what its policies towards Italy and Ireland are: friendly interest but no more. We don't anymore get involved with Italian elections; something could be said for having done so in the immediate post-WWII period. We try in Ireland to be relatively even-handed, even though politicians do try to cater to the IRA proclivities of all too many Irish Catholic Americans. I guess Italy is the proper example. Let Israel be like Italy and our government more indifferent to the Zionist lobby. Pat Buchanan got a lot of flack for his perhaps blunt statement about the Zionist Amen Lobby in Washington but he was probably right. Currently such stalwart exemplars of virtue like Senator D'Amato are catering to the NY Jewish vote by browbeating the Swiss about Jewish assets in Swiss bank vaults. Certainly the Swiss will be found somewhat less than sterling in their doings, but D'Amato's demagoguery is obvious in its political purpose. Let's say Good Luck to Netanyahu and the rest of the Israelis. If Israel is so wonderful why are so many Jewish and possible pseudo-Jewish immigrants from Eastern Europe preferring to come to the United States?<br> 
<I>Norman Ravitch, norman.ravitch@ucr.edu</I>


<hr>
<P>
2/3/97<br>
I never thought I'd say this, but I think Netanyahu is doing a pretty good job. When he was first elected I was convinced his arrogance and zealotry would deliver the Middle East to full-scale warhis election rhetoric was harsh, and he seemed determined to undo the great strives toward peace forged by Prime Ministers Rabin and Peres. But since then he has moderated his approach, and by continuing the peace processdespite the constant fuming of Israel's right winghe is enabling the possibilities of lasting peace in the Middle East and a free Palestine.<br>
<I>Leslie G. Burton</I>

<hr>
<P>
2/3/97<br>

Netanyahu does what Clinton is not capable of doing. Leading his country and doing what his strength of character tells him is best for his country. We in the US would do well to see our national security threatened economically and culturally as the Israelis see theirs threatened militarily. Netanyahu defends his country's right to exist as a Jewish state by confrontational force when necessary, rather than the kinder-gentler sympathetic abetting practiced by the Clinton Administration. I would trade a leader like Netanyahu for Clinton, but I'm sure Israel would pass!<br> 
<I>Dan Shaw, dshaw@nbserv2.dseg.ti.com</I>
<hr>
<hr>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<center>To submit your comments,</center><br>
<center><A HREF="mailto:nronline@ix.netcom.com">click here</a>.</center>
<P>
