<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/09oct95/contents.html">October 9, 1995</A> Myth of the Racist Cabbie: <b>Dinesh D'Souza</b> explains the difference between racism and discrimination, and suggests that some of the latter may be entirely rational.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/25sep95/contents.html">September 25, 1995</A> The Little Engine that Couldn't: <b>Stephen Moore</b> examines the spine of the Republican body politic and wonders whether it will make it through the coming budget battles.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/11sep95/contents.html">September 11, 1995</A> Fear Itself: <b>Rich Lowry</b> scrutizes Democratic charges of Republican laxity on public health matters and finds them lacking. 
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/28aug95/contents.html">August 28, 1995</A> From the Editor: <b>John O'Sullivan</b> on Japanese war crimes, Ross Perot and the GOP, and the effectiveness of Bob Packwood's methods on securing a first date.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/14aug95/contents.html">August 14, 1995</A> Affirmative Inaction: <b>Ramesh Ponnuru</b> laments the GOP's lack of leadership on racial prefrences...The Cigar Revisited: <b>William A. Rusher</b> defends the conservative virtues of a good smoke.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/21july95/contents.html">July 31, 1995</A> The 101st Senator: <b>Rich Lowry</b> gives Bob Dole's inordinately powerful staffer, Sheila Burke, a once over...<b>Jeffrey Hart</b> reviews David Gelernter's <I>1939:The Lost World of the Fair</I> and gives a qualified thumbs up.  
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/10july95/contents.html">July 10, 1995</A> Legalizing Drugs: Just Say Yes: An Interview with <b>Michael S. Gazzaniga</b>...The Gimlet Eye: <b>Andrew Ferguson</b> on Robert McNamara as a Washington phenomenon.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/26june95/contents.html">June 26, 1995</A> Saving Gramm's Campaign: <b>Richard Brookhiser</b> explores the inner workings of a presidential canmpaign...<b>Florence King</b> considers, briefly, America's shrinking attention span. 

