<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>League News - 8/7/96</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#3232CD">
<img src="../images/griffgrn.gif"><br>
<img src="../images/news2.gif"><br>
<p>
<strong>
<FONT SIZE=5>Dole Tax Proposals</FONT></strong><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>They Might Help But They Aren't Sufficient</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Washington, D.C., August 7, 1996 - U.S. savers and investors, individually and collectively, suffer under an oppressive tax system; one that doubles, triples and quadruples the taxes applied to the same investment return or gain.  Whoever labeled investment return or gain as &quot;unearned income&quot; had to have a sinister sense of humor.  Securing a reasonable income from saving and investing is not an easy task, and is one that calls for eternal vigilance.
<P>
Reducing the income tax on investment return by 15% is certainly an improvement but is far short of the proper tax reduction of 100%.  After you have had your wage or salary income taxed, whatever you have left can only be spent or saved.  If you spend it there is no investment income for Uncle Sam to tax year after year thereafter.  If you save it, you are creating economic growth for yourself and everyone else - including the government.  It is this added economic growth, derived solely from increased saving, that creates more jobs, and more production at lower costs, and higher standards of living for everyone - including the saver.  All of this expanded economic activity also creates more tax dollars for Uncle Sam than otherwise collected under the annual income tax as applied to saving.
<P>
You don't have to be a rocket scientist to accept the fact that eliminating the tax on saving will increase our peoples rate of saving significantly.
<P>
Is it any wonder all economists recognize the existing inherent tax bias against saving.  A 15% reduction in that bias against investment income is only a small step in the right direction.
<P>
<HR>
[<a href="/savers"/>Home</a>]
</BODY>
