Investment Account Act (<a href="/savers/library/breaux.html">Mr. Breaux</a>)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/s287.html">S. 287</a> To allow homemakers to get a full IRA deduction.  
(Mrs. Hutchison)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/s488.html">S. 488</a> Flat tax on earned 
income. (Mr. Specter)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/s722.html">S. 722</a> or (<a 
href="/savers/legislation/blcusa.html">Summary</a>) USA Tax Act of 1995 (Mr. 
Domenici and Mr. Nunn)  
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/s807.html">S. 807</a> To allow individuals who have reached age 59 1/2 to 
contribute to an IRA without regard to their compensation. (Mr. Lieberman)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/s959.html">S. 959</a> Capital Formation Act of 1995 (Mr. Hatch)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/s1050.html">S. 1050</a> or (<a 
href="/savers/legislation/blcflat.html">Summary</a>) Freedom and Fairness 
Restoration Act of 1995 (aka: Flat Tax) (Mr. Shelby) 
<br>
</ul>
