<DOCNO>WT20-B16-117</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA031-000656-B029-271</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.atr.org:80/savers/about.html 204.71.237.87 19970209065737 text/html 9848
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 06:58:22 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 05-Mar-96 20:25:57 GMT
Content-length: 9664
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>    
<HEAD>    
<TITLE>League Information</TITLE> 
</HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<body background="/savers/images/white.gif"> 
<center><img src="/savers/images/griffwh.gif"><br>
<img src="/savers/images/logoltwh.gif"><br>
<hr>
<font size=6><b><i><a name="top">League</a> 
Information</i></b></font></center> <hr>
<p>
<FONT size=5><b><a  
name="phil">Philosophy</a></b></FONT>   <hr>  
<P>    
<center><b><i>All of your savings and investments should be tax deductible and tax    
deferred<br>   
until you, or your beneficiary, consume it.</i></b></center><br>   
<p>   
The Savers &amp; Investors League was organized in 1988 by <a    
href="/savers/about.html#tkelly">Tom Kelly</a> who recognized the compelling,    
critical need for increased personal savings and investment to foster healthy economic growth in the     
United States. <br>    
<p>    
Without question, private savings and investment is the  foundation for increased personal and national      
prosperity.  Whether these savings are in bank accounts, stocks, bonds, CDs, IRAs, insurance, annuities,     
pension funds, mutual funds, etc., they constitute the vital capital base needed and utilized by individuals,     
families, businesses, and government.<BR>    
<p>    
 On a personal level, insufficient savings creates uncertainty for future retirement, as well as uncertainty    
as to the family financial resources of home and health care needs and desires.  A diminished supply of     
private capital on a national scale causes interest rates to rise and economic growth to slow. Also,     
wages,jobs, and standards-of-living suffer.<br><br>    
 Disastrously, the government continues to pass or maintain self-defeating, senseless laws that    
limit and penalize tax-deferred savings plans such as IRA's, 401(k) s and pensions.<BR>    
<p>    
The annual income tax imposed upon investment return and    
realized gain needlessly and scandalously decreases  the country's    
vital capital base year after year. Not only do taxpayers suffer,    
the government's tax base is progressively reduced too.<BR>    
<P>    
The Nation must maximize personal savings and investment,    
so that private capital will grow and expand as quickly, and as    
soundly, as possible.<BR>    
<P>    
The Individual Investment Account, Senate Bill   
 <a href="/savers/legislation/s159.html">S. 159</a> and House Bill   
 <a href="/savers/legislation/hr328.html">H.R. 328</a>, accomplishes    
this simple but vital objective.<br>   
<p>   
The League helped develop this legislation and works diligently to secure its    
enactment.  The bipartisan sponsors are: Senator John Breaux</a>, Democrat,   
 Senate Finance Committee, and Representative Jim McCrery, Republican,   
 House Ways &amp; Means Committee.<br>   
<p>   
This simple, straight-forward legislation creates IRA-type accounts that provide -    
<br>   
<ul>   
<li>Unlimited, tax-deductible contributions for everyone<br><br>   
<li>No penalty taxes on any account withdrawal<br><br>   
<li>No forced distributions at any time<br><br>   
<li>No income tax nor estate tax at death<br><br>   
<li>Account holder, or beneficiary, only pay taxes on account withdrawals<br><br>   
</ul>   
<p>   
The Individual Investment Account Act has been described by leading tax economists    
as <i>&quot;one of the boldest, most imaginative, and most constructive pro-growth    
tax initiatives in many years.&quot;</i>   
<p>   
<hr>    
 <FONT size=5><b><a name="obj">Objectives</a></b></FONT><BR>    <hr>   
<P>    
<center><b><i>Your wealth is &quot;wealth&quot; no matter how small or large.<br>    
You must protect it from improper, confiscatory, taxes.</i></b></center><br>    
<p>    
The League's primary objective is to remove the government's senseless     
tax bias against private savings and investments. By building a broad base of voter/taxpayer activists,    
spanning all age groups and income     
levels, the League:<BR>     
<p>    
<ul>    
<li> Works toward the development and adoption of clear, concise, tax laws that    
 promote increased private saving and investing.<BR>    
<br>    
<li> Works with members of Congress and the Administration to support     
or defeat legislation which affects the taxation of private savings and     
investments.<BR>    
<br>    
<li> Communicates with voter/taxpayers, as well as with financial     
institutions, employers, unions, and the media.<br>     
<br>    
<li> Builds coalitions with like-minded groups, unions, and associations.<br>    
<BR>    
<li> Tracks and reports upon relevant legislation as it makes its     
way through the congressional maze.<BR>     
<br>    
<li> Informs the media on current savings and investment taxation issues in     
order to generate broad, public appreciation and understanding     
of this vital subject.<BR>    
</ul>    
<p>  
<hr>    
<FONT size=5><b><a name="sands">Structure and  
Support</a></b></FONT><BR>    <hr>   
   
<P>     
Because the League lobbies Congress on behalf of voter/taxpayers, 
 it is a 501(c)(4) non profit corporation.      
Therefore, contributions to the League are not deductible as charitable contributions for Federal income      
tax purposes. However, contributions to the League may be deductible as an ordinary and necessary      
business expense, or an expense incurred in the production of income.<BR>     
<p> The League's affiliated Savers &amp; Investors Foundation carries out research endeavors that      
explore the impact of taxes on our economy, as well as on taxpayers, our government, and our nation. The      
Foundation is a 501(c)(3) research and educational nonprofit organization.  
Contributions to it are tax     deductible.     
<BR>     
<P>     
Neither the League nor the Foundation have a minimum or     
maximum contribution limit. All contributors choose the contribution     
amount most suitable for themselves. <b>While voluntary contributions     
from all sources are vital to the League's and Foundation's work,     
each voter/taxpayer's active participation via on-going communications     
with his or her Senators and Representative, regardless of contribution     
level, is what really counts.</b>  Members of Congress respond to     
strong constituent interest. As a result of the League's activities,  
savers and investors become an increasingly powerful, focused force  
before Congress and the Administration.<BR>     
<hr>
<p>
<img src="/savers/images/tkellysm.gif"><FONT SIZE=5><B><a name="tkelly">&#32; Tom 
Kelly</a>, President and Founder</B></FONT> <HR> 
<P> 
Tom Kelly, League President and Founder, likes to explain that he is not an actuary, accountant, lawyer or 
economist.  Instead, he describes himself as an &quot;entrepreneurial businessman&quot; within the pension 
and life insurance areas who has &quot;a  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
facility for conceptualizing and implementing new solutions to old problems&quot;.<BR> 
<P> 
He began his career in 1948 as a pension and employee benefits consultant with Towers, Perrin, Forster, 
&amp; Crosby.  In 1962, Tom raised capital to underwrite the First Investment Annuity Company (FIAC).  
The Investment Annuity, invented by Tom, was a  
 
 
policyowner self-directed variable annuity which had never been offered  
by any insurer previously.<BR> <P> 
After fifteen years of product and financial success, the Treasury and  
IRS reversed over 70 favorable rulings issued over prior years to FIAC and other insurer emulators.  FIAC 
sued the Treasury and the IRS for &quot;arbitrary, capricious, and illegal  
acts&quot;.  The D.C. District Court agreed and stated that indeed the  
Treasury and IRS ruling was in fact arbitrary, capricious, illegal, and  
unreasonable.  Furthermore, the court stated that the IRS had usurped the  
power of Congress, and that deference to their  
expertise on this matter was unwarranted.  The Treasury and the IRS appealed.  The Appellate Court didn't 
look at  
 
the merits of the case but ruled that the District Court didn't have  
jurisdiction.  The District Court Judge had previously concluded  
that if FIAC couldn't be  
in District Court, FIAC was being denied due process of law - a  
constitutional matter...<BR> <P> 
FIAC employed Robert Bork, Esq., then a Yale law professor and outstanding  
constitutional scholar, to assist in a Supreme Court petition.  For  
unspecified reasons, the  
Supreme Court did not accept the case.  Thus, the Treasury and IRS won -  
but not on the merits 
 
 of their tax law position.  FIAC was thereupon forced to liquidate in  
1978.<BR> <P> 
It was this encounter with arbitrary, capricious and illegal government  
acts that prompted Tom's strong interest and on-going great concern about  
the misguided  
driving force behind the government's tax policy in regard to saving.<BR> 
<P> 
That same year, 1978, Tom formed Insurer Central Services (ICS) that  
assists  
insurers enter the specialized field of variable annuities and variable life insurance.<BR> 
<P> 
The Savers &amp; Investors League was started in 1988 to educate and  
motivate grass roots voter/taxpayers to challenge and change the way our  
government measures the tax revenue impact of tax deferred savings.   
Towards this end, over the  
intervening years, Tom has worked with legislators, economists, and think tanks to develop legislation that 
meets the proper criteria for the sound taxation of personal saving.<BR> 

<HR> 
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>], [<a href="/savers/member.html">Membership  
Information</a>], [<a href="/savers/about.html#top">Top of Current Document</a>]    
 </BODY>     
     
