VLINK="#6f6f6f" ALINK="#000000"></A>
<center><NOBR><IMG SRC="../images/twtbanner.gif" WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="The Washington Times" border=0>
<A HREF="../aboutNWE.html">
<IMG SRC="images/letters.gif" WIDTH=145 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Letters" border=0></A>
</NOBR>
<IMG SRC="../images/nwe.redrule.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0><BR><NOBR><font size=-1>Published in Washington, D.C.<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>&#009;<B>February 9, 1997 -- Edition</B>&#009;<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>"America's Newspaper"<BR></font></NOBR><A HREF="buttons.3.gif.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap8"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="436,1,519,18" HREF="../watch/watch.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="351,1,428,16" HREF="#linkTOP"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="263,0,345,19" HREF="../stories/exclusive.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="177,1,257,18" HREF="../stories/culture.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="90,0,172,19" HREF="../stories/top.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="2,1,86,18" HREF="../index.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/buttons.3.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=19 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Navigation Bar graphic, see text links below." border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap8" ISMAP></A><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=8><BR><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=520><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="5"><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=325><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><font size=7>Letters to the Editor<BR></font><FONT SIZE=6>Abuse of authority</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Speaker Newt Gingrich flaunted the rules of the House of Representatives. He broke IRS rules for which others have paid substantial fines or served time. Mr. Gingrich admitted wrongdoing and bringing disgrace to the House.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Yet, rather than doing the honorable thing, Mr. Gingrich refuses to step down and chooses instead to hold onto the personal power of the office. Mr. Gingrich's punishment is merely a slap on the wrist.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Representative government has become government representative of, by and for the "Authority Class."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>If the American electorate were to vote on the issue, Mr. Gingrich would be censured and removed from office. This would be reflective of American and family values, which Mr. Gingrich likes to merely talk about toughly and often, while doing the opposite, time and again.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Its politics, stupid!<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Rand Knox<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>San Rafael, California<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Renewed support</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Newt Gingrich must not step down, he must not knuckle under some Democrats' goal of ending conservative trends. America needs Mr. Gingrich's ideas and leadership or our country will slip even deeper into the murky sea of socialistic demise.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>We support Newt Gingrich and, if it's necessary that he pay his "fine" from personal funds, then so be it. However, many of us who have watched his college course in its entirety, must disagree. It was not partisan.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Excuse, for now I must dash out and buy another copy of "To Renew America."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Janice S. Boehmig<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Atlanta, Georgia<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Grin and bury it</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Republicans today remind me of liberals during the Cold War. "If we'd just be nicer to the Democrats then maybe they'd stop hounding Newt Gingrich and we could all live in a universe of peace and harmony."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Whatever happened to kick-butt conservatives who defeated their opponents because they damn well deserved it? <BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Whatever happened to conservatives who were "mean-spirited" enough to consign the Soviet Union to the ash heap of history?<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Frankly, I do not desire peaceful coexistence with the enervation of Democrat statism and the cultural degradation resultant from the democratization of the left's historically extreme species of antiestablishmentarianism. I want to bury it!<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>John Briatico Jr.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Bensenville, Illinois<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>What a nightmare</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>This may not be true, but we hear Newt Gingrich had trouble sleeping the night before the election for House Speaker so he watched a movie about an incredible shrinking man and also one about visiting a nudist colony. The next morning, his wife asked if he'd slept well.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"No, I sure didn't," he replied. "I dreamed I was only three feet tall and visited a nudist colony."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Well, that doesn't seem so bad," his wife said.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"It was though," Mr. Gingrich replied. "Everybody I met looked like David Bonior."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>L.J. Purdy<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Gridley, Kansas<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>A poor judgment<BR>on school choice</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Wisconsin Judge Paul Higginbotham refused to allow the expansion of Milwaukee's school choice program (Jan. 26 edition) by saying it "compels Wisconsin citizens of various religious faiths to support schools with their tax dollars that proselytize students and attempt to inculcate them with beliefs contrary to their own."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>With minimal editing, this statement could also serve as a pretty good description of the way public education operates. After all, without compulsion, what else would induce parents to keep sending their children to schools where costs have skyrocketed at the same time academic standards and performance have declined, where politically correct but historically dubious "history" is taught and Christmas is now just the anniversary of the winter solstice.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Only compulsion could have created an educational bureaucracy so bloated, inefficient and politically driven as ours is, with its enormous cost contributing to an onerous tax burden that leaves the average family with no choice but to send their children to public school.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>No, Judge Higginbotham, I don't buy your argument that expanding school choice to include parochial schools violates the Wisconsin constitution, though it would clearly violate the state's monopoly over the education of its children.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Several years ago I was told that school boards were first created in colonial New England in the late 17th century to preserve orthodoxy. Nothing has changed in three centuries, except the definition of orthodoxy.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>David Taylor<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Easton, Maryland<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Please pass the smelling salts</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Being a recently retired university professor, I particularly enjoyed the column by Thomas Sowell (Jan. 19 edition) on the evolving practice by certain educational institutions of brainwashing the student captive audience in accordance with their own liberal/leftist agendas. Mr. Sowell is my hero for having the courage to buck the tide of leftism in much of the news media and academia.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>To this end, a rather humorous event happened to me a few years ago at an education-related conference. I was seated next to a rather verbose feminist-activist at the culminating conference banquet along with several other legislators.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>After listening to about 20 minutes of her non-stop advocating that the faculty force administrators to adhere to her prescribed agenda, I dropped her a bombshell in order to turn off the faucet. I commented, "if I were president of a university, I would lay down a set of no-nonsense rules and expect them to be followed. The first breach of the rules would earn the perpetrator 25 strokes of the cane. The second would earn 24 hours in the stocks on the campus lawn."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>She looked at me in shock and dismay, while the others at the table attempted unsuccessfully to suppress giggles, and frowningly said, "that's just like a macho male. How could you do that to your poor students?"<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>I promptly replied, "dear madam, I was not referring to the students, I was referring to the faculty!"<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>She sank back in her chair, holding her head as if about to faint, while the surrounding guests broke out in uncontrollable laughter.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>As I write this letter, her reaction reminds me of the well-known television ad where the pompous old lady faints when the country bumpkin says, "would you please pass the jelly?"<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Joseph Plunkett, Ph.D<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Black Rock, Arkansas<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Dale Brown should<BR>share the blame</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>It was difficult to believe that you would waste print on Dale Brown (Jan. 19 edition), who recently resigned as head basketball coach at Louisiana State University because he said he could no longer hide his disgust with the system. Fans at LSU have been hiding their disgust with him for years.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>If college basketball is rotten, Dale Brown should share the blame. Mr. Brown says he arrived here in an old Volkswagen with $800 in his pocket. He can leave in a chauffeur-driven Rolls Royce with perhaps millions in the bank.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>It's hard for me to tell if you wrote this as a serious piece of journalism, or to portray the braying of a jackass.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Goodbye, Dale, don't bother to write.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Med Hogg<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Baton Rouge, Louisiana<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Three dollar Bill</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>On Monday, Jan. 20, 1997, America witnessed the inaugural Bacchanal of William Jefferson Clinton, the man with a bumper-car set of values capable of rebounding from any opposing force to careen in whatever direction offers a path of less resistance.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>There in the nation's capital were food, drink and games of the circus beyond the wildest imaginings of Gaius and Tiberius Gracchi, the Roman emperors who first drew up the Democratic Party's blueprint for voter control. The world will little note nor long remember the inaugural address -- a 20-minute braggadocio in which Mr. Clinton pedaled pre-owned ideas with the glibness of a man selling pre-owned cars.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The entire 14-ball, $43 billion extravaganza brought to mind a paraphrase of the late Ben Hecht -- "Bill Clinton's Washington -- where truth crushed to earth rises again phonier than a three dollar bill."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Dick Mercer<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Nantucket, Massachusetts<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Painful Ponzi</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>I have ended up almost choking on my morning coffee over the last few weeks as I have read about Social Security reform. Where two years ago, the press were telling us all that the Republicans wanted to throw grandma and grandpa out into the street by daring to propose Social Security reform, those same people in the press are now telling us that the nation's economy is doomed unless we enact that reform now. Everyone is beginning to see Social Security for what it really is, the world's largest Ponzi scheme. That "giant sucking sound" we heard a few years ago was Social Security going down the toilet.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Why don't we let each taxpayer decide if they want to be in or out of the Social Security program?  Just let us have control over our money that is currently being put in. I guarantee that I can do better with that money than the government can. A bold plan that cuts the government out of my retirement future, thank you!<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Tim Schmidt<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Williston, North Dakota<FONT SIZE=6><BR><BR>Dembonics</FONT><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>My wife Sue noticed the photograph of Rep. Jim McDermott (page one, Jan. 26 edition) showing his Seattle office door with a sign that states "Cannot Accept Any Gifts." This statement is shown beneath the internationally used symbol of the circle with a diagonal line. This constitutes a double negative. Or is this "Dembonics" for gifts welcome?<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Gary Skidmore<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=0>Johnson City, Tennessee</TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=12><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="../images/vertical.gif" WIDTH=9 HEIGHT=280 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=180><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><A HREF="write.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap9"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="1,3,180,59" HREF="mailto:nated@infi.net"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/write.gif" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="E-mail address: nated@infi.net" border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap9" ISMAP></A><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=6><BR><font size=-1>We welcome your opinions on any topic. Every letter will be considered for publication, but we prefer those of fewer than 250 words. All letters may be edited for clarity and length. For verification purposes, be sure to include your address and a daytime telephone number for your letter to be considered for publication.</font><font size=-1><BR><BR></font><font size=-1>Snail mail your opinion to:<BR></font><font size=-1><B><center>Letters to the Editor<BR>National Weekly Edition<BR>3600 New York Ave., NE<BR>Washington D.C. 20002<BR>or<BR>FAX-line: 202-269-5934<BR>or<BR>Internet mail:<BR><A HREF="mailto:nated@infi.net">nated@infi.net</A><BR></center></B></font></TD></TD></TABLE></TD></TD></TABLE><center><p><a href="#linkTOP">Go back to the top of this article.</A></center></TD></TR>
