<title>Daily Commentary - January 28, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 28, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Atlantic City officials made a shocking discovery last week when
they entered a crumbling house and found 10 children who'd been 
abandoned.

<p>

For three weeks -- <i>three weeks</i> -- these children
were left to fend for themselves with no electricity or running
water.  Drug paraphernalia was found in the house and the smell
of crack cocaine hung in the air.  The children's only sources
of heat, during some of the year's most bitter cold, were two
kerosene heaters.

<p>

Why any parent would leave a child in such miserable conditions
is beyond comprehension.  There's no doubt that Washington has done 
a lot to make conditions in America's inner cities worse.  The 
welfare system has devastated the black family.  And politicians 
have failed to take the drug problem seriously enough, exposing 
more and more children to its deadly effects.

<p>

But at the end of the day, my friends, it's really a problem
of the human heart that leaves children in the cold.  It's a problem
that's beyond the realm of politics, and the answers won't be
found in the solutions of the right or left.  They will only come
with a renewal of the human soul.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

