<title>Daily Commentary - January 21, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 21, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

One of the most important lessons of Watergate is that the abuse
of presidential power is very dangerous.  That's why the latest
reports of the Clinton administration conducting politically-motivated
tax audits are so troubling.

<p>

The IRS is headed by Margaret Milner Richardson, a close friend
of Hillary Clinton.  Miss Richardson is conducting audits of several
high-profile conservative organizations.  Some of these groups
have been characterized as &quot;enemies&quot; by the White House.
What's really fishy about this is not a single comparable liberal
group is being audited.

<p>

Tax audits are intrusive; they drag out for months and cost hundreds
of thousands of dollars in legal fees.  They have the power to
destroy these groups, and they're an awesome weapon in silencing
political opponents.  But it's illegal for any administration
to use the IRS for political purposes.

<p>

That's why we are calling for a Congressional investigation of
the IRS's selection of targets for audit.  Using law enforcement
to punish political opponents is an intolerable abuse of power
in a free country.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwold.html.cgi#current">Last Month's Commentaries</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwdaily.html.cgi#current">This Month's Commentaries</a>]
</b></center>

