<html>

<title>January 8, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 8, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>RIGHT TO KILL NOT OBVIOUS IN CONSTITUTION,</h2>
<h4>CLEAVER NOTES HIGH COURT CONCERNED WITH WHO DECIDES<br>
WHO DIES -- AND WHY</h4></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> In today's euthanasia case before the
U.S. Supreme Court, the justices made the most pro-states' rights
arguments heard in years, noted Family Research Council Director
of Legal Studies Cathy Cleaver on Wednesday. Cleaver attended
the arguments as attorney of record for FRC which filed a brief
in the case.

<p>

&quot;The justices seemed reluctant to seize the power of life
and death. The nature of the justices' questions seemed to indicate
that they were concerned about imposing a blanket ruling on the
complex issue of arming physicians with a right to kill,&quot;
Cleaver said. &quot;The court also relied heavily on the centuries-old
tradition that doctors should be healers and not killers. We agree.&quot;

<p>

For example: Justice David Souter asked the attorney general from
Washington state about how the court could weigh the risks of
empowering physicians with a right to kill and how it could be
controlled. The attorney general replied that we can look at the
Netherlands and Germany and see that death could not be contained
... it's been &quot;tried and failed.&quot;

<p>

(Editor's note: Family Research Council's amicus brief dealt with
the historical record of the culture of euthanasia -- so called
&quot;good death&quot; -- in Germany which was expanded from the
killing of the handicapped, elderly and mentally ill to the killing
of others deemed undesirable.)

<p>

Justice Souter commented that the court might want to wait until
it could understand the ramifications of such a decision. Justice
Stephen Breyer, talking about what he learned in the many amicus
briefs, noted that good pain control was available and that almost
all of the 25 percent of people who die in pain, do so needlessly.
The justice asked whether it was right to assume that if we create
a right to assisted suicide, will that not be a disincentive to
improve pain care? Justice Breyer got into the cost of medical
care, mentioning that it would certainly be cheaper to give a
lethal dose than to give aggressive treatment.

<p>

Cleaver noted, &quot;The justices as a whole were very concerned
about whether giving physicians the power to kill was something
for the courts to decide at all or something for states to decide
democratically after discussion and study.&quot;

<p>

Along those lines, Justice Antonin Scalia noted that those favoring
physician-assisted death claim that it would be confined to the
terminally ill, in insufferable pain, who competently request
death. He asked, if you want to legalize a physician's ability
to kill, why would the U.S. Constitution narrowly define those
with a right to die? He asked, if pain gives a person the right
to die, why should the line be drawn with the terminally ill?
Why should those who will be in pain for a 10-year illness be
denied? By what reasoning do you prevent the death right from
expanding?

<p>

&quot;The High Court is clearly weighing the tough questions surrounding
granting physicians the power to kill. There is no greater issue
facing a people than who has the power to take life. It is of
paramount importance that all Americans can trust that the medical
profession is devoted to saving life -- not destroying it,&quot;
Cleaver said.

<p>

<center><h4>FOR MORE INFORMATION OR INTERVIEWS,<br>
CONTACT THE FRC MEDIA OFFICE AT (202) 393-2100.</h4></center>

<p>

