<title>Ed Facts</title>

<body background="/townhall/FRC/images/bckgnd7.jpg" text="#ff0000" 
vlink="#000000">

<center><h1>ED FACTS</h1>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/edfacts/pencil.gif">
</center>

<p><b>
It's an alarming trend. Again and again, Washington increases its 
influence over American education. Goals 2000 ... an ever-bigger 
Department of Education ... new sex education plans ... national 
history standards ... more and more rules. How to keep up with it all? 
Subscribe to <i><b>Ed Facts</b></i>, the Family Research Council 
weekly fax report analyzing breaking education news in the nation's 
capitol and around the country. You'll find out whom to contact to 
make your voice heard and what to watch for in your local school. 
<p>
If you are interested in receiving <i><b>Ed Facts</b></i> at your 
home, school or office, call our toll-free number at 1-800-225-4008, and 
mention that you found us on the internet. 
Or, you can subscribe to <i><b>Ed Facts</b></i> via our on-line 
<a href="/townhall/FRC/subscribe/subscribe.html.cgi">
subscription form</a>. Either way, make sure you subscribe because we want 
to keep you up to date on the latest education issues!
<p>
This week's report is displayed below, and <a href="/townhall/FRC/edfacts/edfctold.html">last week's issue</a> is still available as well.
</b><p>

<hr width=60% size=3 noshade><p>

<center><h2>February 7 Report</h2>
<h4>(Will be updated on Friday, February 14)</h4></center>

<p><hr width=60% size=3 noshade><p>

<font size=+1>

<center><h3>SAD STATE OF EDUCATION</h3></center>

<p>

In his fifth State of the Union address,
President Bill Clinton referred to education as his &quot;number
one priority over the next four years.&quot;  Neatly packaging
it as a 10-point &quot;new-and-improved&quot; solution, Clinton
issued a call for pouring more money into failed government education
programs.

<p>

<u><b>1.  National standards.  National testing in 4th grade reading, 
8th grade math:</b></u> &quot;A national crusade
for education standards -- not federal standards, but national
standards....  <I><B>Every state and school must shape the curriculum
to reflect these standards and train teachers to lift students
up to them</B></I>&quot; [emphasis added].  Forget &quot;voluntary.&quot;
This means every U.S. history teacher must use the <I>National
Standards for United States History</I>.  These standards left
out George Washington's presidency and the U.S. landing on the
moon, but included Madonna and the <I>Challenger</I> shuttle disaster.

<p>

<u><b>2.  National Board for Professional Teaching Standards 
(NBPTS):</b></u> When NBPTS, a board to certify &quot;master teachers,&quot; 
lobbied for federal funding in the late 1980's, it was described as a
teachers union pet.  Chester Finn commented that this &quot;pork
barrel project...set a precedent:  federal aid to a professional
standards board.  If the bill passes [it did], we can expect other
professions and trades to then demand their due [we have -- in
the National Skill Standards Act of Goals 2000].&quot;  As Clinton
points out, only 500 teachers have sought NBPTS certification
since 1995.  As an incentive, the Clinton budget includes funding
for 100,000 more to seek national certification.

<p>

<u><b>3. America Reads Initiative:</b></u> If 825,000 K-3 
classroom teachers, 100,000 Title I teachers and
325,000 special education teachers (almost half of whom have at
least a Masters degree) have only attained a 60 percent success
rate in teaching children to read by the end of third grade, how
will an army of 1,000,000 part-time, half-trained Americorps &quot;volunteers&quot;
do it? Mr. President, we won't settle for your national standard
that all children should be reading by the end of third grade.
We have higher expectations.  We want kids to be reading by the
end of first grade with the help of their classroom teachers who
are paid to teach them.  These kids aren't failures, but the reading
methods they've been taught are.  Reading is not a mysterious
guessing game, but a systematic decoding of the sounds letters
make.  If federal funding can't seem to accomplish the first purpose
of education -- teaching kids to read -- how can we trust any
portion of education to it?

<blockquote>
&quot;This is also a challenge
to every teacher and every 
principal. <i><b>You must 
use these tutors</b></i> to help 
your students read.&quot; 
-- Pres. Clinton
</blockquote>

<p>

<u><b>4. Early Childhood Education:</b></u> &quot;Learning 
begins in the first days of life.&quot;  Just how early, Mr. Clinton? 
This week's <I>TIME</I> magazine cover story (2/03/97) explores the
growing child's brain and points to important developments that
occur before birth.  &quot;At birth a baby's brain contains 100
billion neurons, roughly as many nerve cells as there are stars
in the Milky Way.&quot;  Perhaps the concern for early childhood
education and brain development will lead to a reconsideration
of treatment of children prior to birth.

<p>

<u><b>5. Transferring Between Public Schools and Charter Schools:</b></u> 
What Clinton calls school choice is not parental choice in education.
Under his plan, parents could only transfer their children to
another <I>public</I> school.  And when Clinton proposes increased 
funding to create more charter schools, he's missing the point. Charter 
schools are only an advantage if they cost less and have more freedom
than regular public schools.  Because charter schools are actually
public schools, they can provide a back door to more government
control of education if they increase the public share of the
education market.

<p>

<u><b>6. Character Education:</b></u> Clinton called for uniforms, 
curfews, truancy laws, zero tolerance for guns and drugs in schools 
and labeled it &quot;character education.&quot;
But Representative J. C. Watts (R-Okla.), in his response to
the State of the Union address, defined character as doing what's
right when no one is watching.  Such character can only be taught
when curriculum is edifying and when school authorities are respectable
as well as respectful of other authorities in a child's life,
like parents and the church.

<p>

<u><b>7. School Construction:</b></u> To accommodate the anticipated 
surge in school-age children population
over the next decade, Clinton proposed a $5 billion federal subsidy
for school construction.  But even perennial supporters of federal
spending on education have been reluctant to cede the responsibility
of school construction to the federal government.  &quot;Isn't
construction a state and local issue?&quot; asked one state superintendent
last fall at a Council of Chief State School Officers (CCSSO)
conference (<I>Education Daily</I>, 11/12/96).  Compliance with
federal education mandates has weakened many a local school district
budget.  Let's get to the root of the problem rather than putting
in for new federal funding.

<p>

<u><b>8. Aid for Post-Secondary Education:</b></u> &quot;We must make 
the 13th and 14th years of education -- at least two years of college 
-- just as universal in America by
the 21st century as a high school education is today....&quot;
The old adage, &quot;quality, not quantity,&quot; has some relevance
in education.  By universalizing community college will students
simply be learning in 14 years what they used to learn in 12?

<p>

Former York College president Robert
V. Iosue points out &quot;that more aid will most assuredly jack
the tuition even higher.&quot;  We should &quot;repair the foundation&quot;
of elementary and secondary education, he says, and &quot;stop
gilding the steeple&quot; (<I>Wash. Times</I>, 2/05/97).  If Clinton
supports tax breaks that allow choice of daycare and college,
why doesn't he allow parents to choose their children's school
in between?

<p>

<u><b>9. Lifelong Learning:</b></u> Listening to Clinton speak, 
one wonders if anyone would learn anything without federal involvement 
in education.  The fact is, we do learn throughout our lifetime and 
we don't need federal programs to do it.

<p>

<u><b>10. Internet Access in Every Classroom, Library ... and Home:</b></u> 
Not too long ago, people argued that educational programming on 
television would stamp out illiteracy. While technology can be a useful 
tool, it is not the ultimate solution some make it out to be.  The 
federal government can best promote technological advances in education 
by removing its bureaucratic presence from the playing field of education
so that individuals, families and smaller, sprier groups can carry
the ball farther, faster.

<p>

<b>All told, Clinton wants to spend
$51 billion on education next year.  More federal spending, more
programs.  America has been there and done that, and our schools
are the worse for it.  A ten-point plan telling how to shift money
and power from Washington, D.C., back to parents and local leaders
would be an outline for true reform.</b>

<p><hr width=50%><p>

<font size=-1>
<i><b>Ed Facts</b> is a weekly facsimile publication of Family
Research Council, 801 G St., N.W., Washington, D.C.
20001.  Phone:  202-393-2100; FAX:  202-393-2134; Legislative
Hotline: 202-783-HOME; Order line:  800-225-4008; Internet Site:
http://www.frc.org.  Suggested annual donation for <b>Ed
Facts</b>: $25.</i>


