<html>

<title>Legislative Hotline</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.gif"></center>

<p>

The Family Research Council has implemented a Legislative Hotline.  By dialing
<b>1-202-783-HOME</b>, you will access current information on pending family
issues in Washington, D.C., via telephone.  The hotline is updated every 
Friday evening.

<p>

Just in case you missed it, make sure to read 
<a href="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotlnold.html">last week's message</a> so that 
you can stay current on the latest issues that affect you and your family.

<p>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/images/redline.gif"></center>
<p>

<center><h2>This Week's Message (February 7)</h2></center>

<p>

Welcome to the FRC information line. This message will be updated
Friday, Feb. 14th at the close of business.

<p>

<h3>Issue One. The State of the Union.</h3>

<p>

In response to the
State of the Union address by President Clinton and remarks by
Oklahoma Rep. J.C. Watts on Tuesday, February 4, FRC President
Gary Bauer called on Congress to draw on the strengths of both
presentations to produce an agenda that will serve the cause of
family and cultural renewal.  Although the President spoke of
mainstream concerns, education, drugs, crime, and community empowerment,
his remarks were generally silent on cultural issues of right
and wrong which are at the core of our nation's social ills.

<p>

In the days to come FRC will examine the President's forthcoming
detailed proposals and some of his current proposals including
an increase in federal funding of the National Endowment for the
Arts (NEA), Internet access, and education.  If we truly want
to challenge the nation's artists, we must ask them to create
their works with the same independence of energy and spirit that
animated our nation's writers and painters for centuries before
the advent of the NEA.  Continuing this federal handout to a favored
few is morally wrong and unnecessary, at best.  Furthermore, access
to the Internet for every American 12 year old from a computer
in every home is not merely an issue of fiber optics, but of the
fiber of our people.  The President's goal simply cannot and will
not be reached if the problem of pervasive pornography on the
Internet is not resolved.  In this regard, what the president's
appointees on the Supreme Court do with the Communications Decency
Act will make all the difference.  The same can be said for most
of the family values agenda; neither strong rhetoric or wide laws
will matter much if our courts continue to erase what our elected
leaders have enacted and signed. On education, President Clinton
appeared as a forward-thinking leader by focusing on education,
but instead he exposed his belief in big government.  Last year
President Clinton declared the era of big government was over,
however, he's proposing a $51 billion initiative that would massively
expand the federal role in education.  In the past 18 years since
the creation of the Department of Education, test scores have
gone down, the quality of education has declined and too many
schools have become unsafe for students and teachers alike. All
this despite a tripling of its budget. There's no connection between
government spending and educational improvement.  But there is
a connection between government spending and government control
and Congress should look for ways to increase parent's control
instead of government's.  It's the only way we can really reform
education.

<p>

Perhaps the biggest disappointment of the night was the president's
failure to speak the plain truth about the deterioration of human
rights, specifically in the vast nation of China.  This oversight
made his strong words about emerging democracies in Central America
and Eastern Europe ring hollow.  Bauer pointed out, the Berlin
Wall didn't come down because of some amorphous sense of 'inevitability.'
It came down because leaders like Ronald Reagan and Pope John
Paul II had the moral courage to stand up to oppressive tyrants.
Active moral leadership is needed today on behalf of the more
than one billion men, women, and children who are systematically
and cruelly abused by a despotic regime in Communist China. The
United States has an obligation to provide this moral leadership
and act upon these violations of fundamental liberties.

<p>

<h3>Issue Two. Foreign Aid Abortion Vote.</h3>

<p>

The first pro-life
vote of the 105th Congress will take place on Thursday, February
13th, when members of the House and perhaps the Senate decide
whether or not to release an additional $123 million to international
organizations, many of which perform and promote abortions as
a method of family planning. Pro-life Members in the House will
also seek a vote on an <I>alternative</I> measure, sponsored by
pro-life leader Chris Smith (R-NJ), which will release money for
family planning but <I>only if</I> groups are <I>not</I> allowed
to promote or perform abortions.  As a result of President Clinton's
executive order, issued during his first week in office, taxpayer-financed
groups can not only lobby foreign governments for changes in their
abortion laws but can also perform elective abortions.   FRC urges
you to call your Congressman and Senators and urge them to vote
AGAINST the Clinton administration's resolution.  House members
should also be urged to vote FOR the abortion limitation proposed
by pro-life Congressman Chris Smith.

<p>

Thank you for calling the FRC Legislative Hotline.

<p>
